window.GD_ASSIST={"lessons":[{"f":"start-here/00-how-to-use.html","t":"How to use this course","tn":"Start Here","k":"0","x":"Why this course exists · The shape of the journey · What every lesson gives you · The five habits that make this work · What you need (spoiler: almost nothing) · This is a path : go top to bottom, and nothing depends on so · The standard for “done” is “could I explain this, and ship i · Every lesson has the same seven parts; the example, quiz, an · Type code yourself, predict before running, struggle before  · You need only a browser now, and a free Google account soon.","s":"Two minutes of orientation that will make every lesson after this one land harder. Read it once, then never worry about “am I doing this right?” again."},{"f":"start-here/01-setup.html","t":"Your free, no-cost toolkit","tn":"Start Here","k":"0","x":"Why we need a place to run code · Google Colab, explained from zero · Run your first cell (do this now) · A first taste of real AI code · Two things worth knowing about Colab · A notebook runs code in small cells ; you run one, see its o · Google Colab runs notebooks in your browser on Google’s comp · Run a cell with Shift + Enter ; install free packages with ! · Colab auto-saves to Google Drive, and offers a free GPU (Run · Running locally with Python + Ollama is a fine, free, offlin · notebook · cell · Google Colab · GPU","s":"In the next five minutes you’ll be running real Python in your browser — no installs, no credit card, no setup headaches. Let’s get your free workshop ready."},{"f":"start-here/02-python-primer.html","t":"The Python you'll actually use","tn":"Start Here","k":"0","x":"Why a little Python — and only a little · 1 · Values and variables · 2 · Strings and f-strings (the most important one) · 3 · Lists · 4 · Dictionaries · 5 · Functions · 6 · Loops · 7 · Making decisions with if · 8 · Importing libraries · Putting it together · Variables name values with = . Strings are text; f-strings d · Lists [...] are ordered collections (counting from 0). Dicts · Functions ( def ) take arguments and return a value. Loops ( · Indentation defines what’s “inside” a function, loop, or if. · import brings in libraries ; use their tools with a dot, lik · value · variable · string · f-string · list · dictionary · function · arguments · return value · for-loop · if-statement · libraries · traceback","s":"You don’t need to “learn Python” to start. You need about eight small ideas, and you’ll meet every one of them here, with runnable examples. Come back to this page any time something looks unfamiliar."},{"f":"start-here/03-python-fluency.html","t":"Python fluency: the next layer","tn":"Start Here","k":"0","x":"Why this, and why now · 1 · Comprehensions: transform a list in one line · 2 · Dictionary moves you’ll use daily · 3 · Building real prompts: multi-line and joined · 4 · Functions with sensible defaults · 5 · Safe by default: try / except and JSON · Putting it together · Live demo: build a prompt template · Comprehensions [f(x) for x in items] transform a list in one · .get(key, default) reads a maybe-missing key without crashin · Build prompts with triple-quoted strings and \"\\n\".join(list) · Default arguments make functions simple to call yet configur · try/except + json.loads is how you survive flaky calls and m · list comprehension · default argument · try/except","s":"The primer gave you the eight basics. This lesson adds the next handful of moves that show up in almost every piece of real GenAI code — comprehensions, dictionary tricks, multi-line prompts, safe JSON, and graceful error handling. Still beginner-paced, still $0 ."},{"f":"start-here/04-python-drills.html","t":"Python drills","tn":"Start Here","k":"0","x":"How to get the most from these · Drill 1 — Filter a list (comprehension) · Drill 2 — Count things (frequency dict) · Drill 3 — Build a messages list · Drill 4 — A tiny chunker · Drill 5 — Read a nested field safely · Drill 6 — Keyword search (the seed of retrieval) · Transforming and filtering lists with comprehensions (Drills · Building and counting with dicts , including safe nested rea · Assembling the messages list-of-dicts by hand (Drill 3) — th · Writing a chunker and a keyword retriever — miniature versio","s":"Reading code isn’t the same as writing it. These six short drills move the patterns from 0.3 and 0.4 into your fingers. Each is a real mini-task you’ll see again later in the course. Try each one in a free Colab cell before opening the solution."},{"f":"track1/01-what-is-an-llm.html","t":"What is a language model?","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"Why this is the first thing to learn · The one move: predict the next token · Where the “knowledge” comes from: training · Why ChatGPT feels different from a “next-word guesser” · An LLM does one thing: given the tokens so far, output a pro · It generates text by sampling one token, appending it, and r · It learned by predicting the next token over trillions of wo · Frozen weights ⇒ a knowledge cutoff and no memory of past ch · Chat assistants are base models instruction-tuned to follow  · language model · large language model · parameters · tokens · autoregression · training · self-supervised learning · weights · inference · base model · instruction-tuned · chat","s":"Almost everything confusing about AI gets clear once you understand the one simple thing these models actually do. It’s not magic, it’s not a search engine, and it’s not a database. It’s a next-word guesser — and that idea, taken seriously, explains the rest of this course."},{"f":"track1/02-tokens.html","t":"Tokens & tokenization","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"Why you can’t skip tokens · Why chop words into pieces at all? · See it for yourself · The rules of thumb that pay off daily · A token is a chunk of text (often a word-piece); the model’s · Sub-word tokenization (e.g. BPE ) balances a manageable voca · Tokens are the unit of cost, context limits, and latency — n · Rule of thumb: ~4 characters ≈ 1 token in English; code and  · Quirks to remember: leading spaces belong to tokens , and mo · token · vocabulary · tokenizer · byte-pair encoding","s":"Tokens are the units everything is measured in — your costs, your context limits, your latency. They also explain a pile of “why did it do that?” behaviors. Spend twenty minutes here and a lot of mysteries dissolve."},{"f":"track1/03-embeddings.html","t":"Embeddings: meaning as vectors","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"Why embeddings have to exist · Measuring “similar”: cosine similarity · Token ids are arbitrary labels ; embeddings are meaningful v · An embedding model turns text into one vector (hundreds–thou · Cosine similarity measures the angle between vectors: +1 sim · Embeddings capture meaning, not word overlap — paraphrases w · This is the engine of semantic search and RAG : store doc ve · embedding · vector · dimension · embedding model · cosine similarity","s":"This is the idea that makes search, RAG, recommendations, and clustering possible. Once you can turn meaning into numbers, you can do math on meaning — and a huge amount of applied AI is exactly that."},{"f":"track1/04-context-attention.html","t":"Context windows & attention","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"Why there’s a limit at all · The catch with “just use a huge window” · How the model uses the context: attention · Watch attention resolve a pronoun · The context window is the max tokens a model handles at once · Chat “memory” is just the whole conversation re-sent each tu · Bigger windows aren’t free: more cost, more latency , and th · Attention lets each token weigh how much every other token m · Position matters : put key instructions where the model reli · context window · attention · transformer · self-attention","s":"Two ideas that decide what your model can actually do in practice: how much it can hold in mind at once (the context window), and how it figures out which of those words matter (attention). Get these and you’ll design prompts and systems that work with the model instead of against it."},{"f":"track1/05-sampling.html","t":"Sampling & decoding","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"Why this is a separate, tunable step · Play with all three at once · Which settings for which job · Decoding is a separate, tunable step from the model: same di · Greedy = always the top token (deterministic). Temperature s · Top-k keeps the k most likely tokens; top-p keeps the smalle · Use low temperature for facts/code/JSON , higher for brainst · For reproducible outputs, use temperature 0 (and a seed if a · decoding · sampling · Greedy decoding · Temperature · Top-k · Top-p · nucleus sampling · seed · logits · softmax","s":"The model hands you a probability for every possible next token. Choosing one is a separate step with its own knobs — temperature, top-k, top-p. These are the settings you’ll tune most often, and the difference between a reliable extractor and a creative writer is often just these numbers."},{"f":"track1/06-capabilities-limits.html","t":"What LLMs can & can't do","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"Why limits matter more than capabilities · Hallucination, demystified · The knowledge cutoff · The good news: every limit has an engineering answer · Limits flow from one fact: the model predicts plausible toke · LLMs are strong at transforming text you provide , weak at r · Hallucination is the mechanism working as designed; confiden · The knowledge cutoff means recent events and private data mu · Every limit has a fix: ground (RAG), tools, evals, guardrail · hallucination · knowledge cutoff","s":"This is the lesson that keeps you employed. Knowing exactly where these models shine and where they quietly fail is the difference between a demo that wows and a product that embarrasses you in front of users. It’s also the most-probed area in interviews."},{"f":"track1/07-interview.html","t":"Interview check: How LLMs Work","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · Next-token prediction & autoregression — in one breath. · Tokens: what they are, the ~4-chars rule, and why letter-cou · Embeddings + cosine similarity, and why they power search/RA · Context window: the shared budget, truncation, “lost in the  · Temperature & top-p, and the settings for extraction vs. bra · Hallucination: the mechanism, confidence ≠ correctness, and  · Knowledge cutoff → supply private/fresh data via RAG, not me","s":"Fundamentals are the most-tested area in applied-GenAI interviews, because they reveal whether you actually understand the tools or just use them. Here are the questions teams really ask, with strong answers and what each one is secretly probing."},{"f":"track1/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: Watch a prediction happen","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"Text becoming tokens — the units the model actually reads. · Tokens becoming vectors , so meaning turns into arithmetic. · Attention reaching back to decide which earlier words matter · A probability distribution over every possible next token. · Sampling — one draw, shaped by temperature. · The token appended, and the whole loop running again.","s":"Everything Track 1 explained — tokens, embeddings, attention, probabilities, sampling — is one loop that runs over and over. Here it is, running, with nothing hidden. Press play and watch a single word get chosen."},{"f":"track1/lab.html","t":"Lab: Build a mini language model","tn":"How LLMs Work","k":"1","x":"Step 1 — Tokenize · Step 2 — Learn what follows what · Step 3 — Sample with a temperature · Step 4 — Generate (autoregression) · A tokenizer that turns text into the units a model actually  · A next-token model — a probability table learned from data. · A softmax + temperature sampler , the real creativity dial. · An autoregressive loop — the mechanism behind every LLM resp · temperature","s":"You’ve learned how the engine works. Now build one. In about forty lines of plain Python you’ll write a tokenizer, a tiny next-token model, and a temperature sampler — then watch it generate text. Everything here runs right in this page ."},{"f":"track2/01-anatomy.html","t":"Anatomy of a prompt","tn":"Prompt Engineering","k":"2","x":"Why prompt engineering is the first tool you reach for · The parts of a well-built prompt · Build a prompt, part by part · A reusable helper (free, local) · Be specific. Specificity narrows the model’s probability dis · Give a role. “You are a senior security reviewer” shifts voc · Show the output format. State it exactly — “Reply with only  · Provide the context. Don’t rely on memory; paste the ticket, · Give it an out. “If the answer isn’t in the context, say ‘I  · Prompt engineering · prompt · messages · role · system message · user messages · assistant messages","s":"Prompting is the cheapest, fastest way to change what a model does — no training, no infrastructure, just words. Before you reach for RAG or fine-tuning, a well-built prompt solves a surprising fraction of problems. This lesson gives you the parts and the principles."},{"f":"track2/02-few-shot.html","t":"Few-shot prompting","tn":"Prompt Engineering","k":"2","x":"Why showing beats telling · Watch examples do three jobs at once · Representative & diverse. Cover the real range of inputs, no · Include edge cases. One “mixed” or “I don’t know” example de · Format examples identically. Any inconsistency in your examp · Watch label balance. If every example is “positive,” the mod · Mind the cost. Examples are tokens in every request — use th · zero-shot · few-shot · one-shot · in-context learning","s":"The single highest-leverage upgrade to most prompts isn’t better wording — it’s a few good examples. Showing the model exactly what you want, with two or three demonstrations, often does what paragraphs of instruction can’t."},{"f":"track2/03-chain-of-thought.html","t":"Chain-of-thought & reasoning","tn":"Prompt Engineering","k":"2","x":"Why blurting fails · Feel it on a trick question · Chain-of-thought = make the model reason step by step before · It works because each step becomes context the final answer  · Zero-shot CoT = “Let’s think step by step”; few-shot CoT = s · Use the “reason, then put the answer on a parseable last lin · Reasoning is still generated text — verify high-stakes answe · Chain-of-thought · zero-shot CoT · few-shot CoT · self-consistency","s":"For anything multi-step — math, logic, planning, careful analysis — one tweak reliably boosts accuracy: ask the model to reason before it answers. It’s simple, it’s backed by how the engine works, and it’s a staple of real prompts."},{"f":"track2/04-structured-output.html","t":"Structured output & JSON","tn":"Prompt Engineering","k":"2","x":"Why structured output is non-negotiable for products · Getting JSON reliably: four levers · Validate it yourself · Software needs machine-readable output ; JSON is the default · Get reliable JSON with four levers: specify the shape, use a · Validate values, not just syntax — check required fields, ty · The production pattern is a generate → validate → retry-with · Tools like pydantic turn a schema into one-line validation;  · JSON · Structured output · schema · Validation · Constrained decoding","s":"The moment you put an LLM inside software , you need its output in a shape code can read. This lesson is how you turn a chatty model into a reliable component — the bridge between “cool demo” and “shipped feature.”"},{"f":"track2/05-patterns.html","t":"Patterns & anti-patterns","tn":"Prompt Engineering","k":"2","x":"Why a playbook beats cleverness · The patterns toolkit · The anti-patterns (and their fixes) · Lint your own prompt · Role — set the stance. Task — say exactly what to do. · Context , fenced with delimiters — supply the data and separ · Examples — show the format; format spec — pin the output sha · Reasoning for multi-step tasks (CoT); decompose if it’s big. · An out — permit “I don’t know”; and put the key instruction  · prompt injection","s":"Everything in this track distilled into a playbook: the reusable moves pros reach for, and the traps that quietly wreck prompts. Internalize this and prompt-writing becomes a checklist, not a guessing game."},{"f":"track2/06-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Prompting","tn":"Prompt Engineering","k":"2","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · The five parts of a prompt, and system vs. user placement. · Few-shot: why it works, how to choose examples, the bias tra · Chain-of-thought: the mechanism, when to skip it, why not to · Reliable JSON: specify → JSON mode → validate → retry, and s · The pattern toolkit and the anti-patterns — and the symptom→ · Prompt injection and the delimiter defense. · When prompting stops being enough (the ladder to RAG and fin","s":"Prompting questions probe whether you can make a model reliable , not just clever. Interviewers want to hear patterns, trade-offs, and debugging instincts. Here’s the set to rehearse."},{"f":"track2/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: Watch a prompt get reliable","tn":"Prompt Engineering","k":"2","x":"A prompt as components , not a magic sentence. · Each component removing one specific class of failure . · The difference between almost-parseable and parseable .","s":"A prompt isn't magic words — it's a set of components, each removing a specific way the model can disappoint you. Watch a bare instruction become a production prompt, and watch three sample runs stop disagreeing."},{"f":"track2/lab.html","t":"Lab: Build a prompt engine","tn":"Prompt Engineering","k":"2","x":"Step 1 — Templates, not strings · Step 2 — Teach by example (few-shot) · Step 3 — Ask for JSON, then survive the reply · Step 4 — Validate before you trust · A template engine — prompts generated from data, edited in o · A few-shot builder that teaches by demonstration. · A tolerant parser that salvages JSON from chatty replies. · A validator that rejects the right-shaped-but-wrong answers.","s":"Prompts stop being strings you paste and start being code you can test . You’ll build a template engine, a few-shot builder, and the parse-and-validate layer that turns a model’s chattiness into data your program can trust."},{"f":"track3/01-why-rag.html","t":"Why RAG exists","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"The problem RAG solves · How it works, at a glance · When to use RAG (and when not to) · RAG fixes the LLM’s cutoff/private-data/hallucination limits · The loop: embed the query → retrieve nearest chunks → put th · It changes the input, not the weights — so updating knowledg · Choose among long-context, RAG, and fine-tuning : RAG for la · RAG’s ceiling is retrieval quality — if the right chunk isn’ · Retrieval-Augmented Generation · knowledge base · Grounding · Retrieval","s":"This is the technique that turns a general-purpose model into your expert — answering from your documents, your policies, today’s data — with citations you can check. It’s the single most common architecture in production GenAI, and it’s built entirely from things you already understand."},{"f":"track3/02-chunking.html","t":"Chunking strategies","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Why chunking decides everything downstream · The size trade-off · Strategies, from crude to smart · See chunking happen · The chunk is the unit of retrieval — chunking decides what c · Use overlap so ideas spanning a boundary survive intact in a · Chunk size is a trade-off : too small fragments context, too · Prefer recursive/structural splitting (respect paragraphs, h · Attach metadata (source, id, section) to every chunk from th · chunks · chunk · Chunk size · Overlap","s":"Retrieval doesn’t fetch documents — it fetches chunks . How you cut your text into chunks quietly determines whether the right information can ever be found. This is the most underrated lever in RAG, and the easiest to get wrong."},{"f":"track3/03-embeddings-retrieval.html","t":"Embeddings for retrieval","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Retrieval is embedding similarity at scale · Choosing an embedding model · Retrieval = cosine similarity between query and chunk embedd · Same embedding model for documents and queries — different m · Normalize vectors so the fast dot product equals cosine simi · Pick a model on quality vs. speed, max sequence length (chun · Some models need query/passage prefixes — read the model car · embedding model · index time · query time · normalizes","s":"You already understand embeddings (Track 1.3). Here you put them to work as the search engine of RAG — turning every chunk into a point in meaning-space once, then finding the nearest points to each question in milliseconds."},{"f":"track3/04-vector-databases.html","t":"Vector databases & indexes","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Why a special database · What’s stored, and why metadata matters · The index family (intuition) · Exact or approximate? · Vector DBs add fast ANN search, metadata filtering, and pers · ANN trades a little recall for a lot of speed — the central  · Records are (id, vector, metadata, text) ; metadata filterin · HNSW (graph) is the common default; IVF (clusters) suits hug · Free options: Chroma, FAISS, Qdrant, Weaviate, pgvector — sa · vector database · index · metadata filtering · persistence · approximate nearest neighbor · recall","s":"Brute-force cosine over a NumPy array is perfect — until you have a million chunks and need answers in 20 milliseconds. Vector databases make retrieval fast, filterable, and durable. Here’s what they actually do, and the one trade-off you must understand."},{"f":"track3/05-retrieval-reranking.html","t":"Retrieval & reranking","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Why “similar” isn’t “best” · See the funnel and the reorder · Bi-encoders are fast but blunt (independent embeddings); cro · Two-stage retrieval : bi-encoder fetches many (recall), cros · You only rerank the shortlist (e.g., 50 → 5), which keeps th · Reranking is often a bigger quality win than a bigger LLM ,  · Tune two numbers: how many to fetch (stage-1 recall) and how · reranker · bi-encoder · cross-encoder · two-stage retrieval · recall · precision · Maximal Marginal Relevance","s":"Vector search is fast but a little blunt — it ranks by similarity, which isn’t the same as relevance. Reranking adds a second, smarter pass that reads each candidate against the query and reorders for quality. This two-stage pattern is one of the biggest, cheapest wins in RAG."},{"f":"track3/06-hybrid-search.html","t":"Hybrid search","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Why one kind of search isn’t enough · Which method wins when · Dense catches meaning/synonyms; sparse (BM25) catches exact  · They fail in opposite cases, so hybrid search (run both, fus · RRF fuses by rank, sidestepping the fact that dense and spar · Hybrid especially helps with identifiers, jargon, and mixed  · Best pipeline: hybrid retrieve → rerank → ground . · Dense retrieval · Sparse retrieval · BM25 · Hybrid search · fuses · Reciprocal Rank Fusion","s":"Semantic search has a blind spot: exact strings. Product codes, names, error IDs, rare jargon — embeddings blur them together. Keyword search nails them but misses paraphrases. Hybrid search runs both and fuses the results, so you stop choosing between meaning and precision."},{"f":"track3/07-grounding-citations.html","t":"Grounding & citations","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Retrieval isn’t enough on its own · The grounded-prompt recipe · Retrieval supplies evidence; grounding forces the model to u · Recipe: number the chunks, instruct “only from context + cit · Abstention is a feature — “not in the documents” beats a con · Verify citations programmatically; don’t assume a cited chun · Citations turn answers from “trust me” into “here’s the sour · Grounding · Faithfulness · Citations · Abstention · faithfulness · answer relevance","s":"Retrieval found the right text. Now make the model actually use it, cite it, and admit when the answer isn’t there. This is where RAG converts retrieved chunks into a trustworthy, verifiable answer — and where a sloppy prompt can throw away all your retrieval work."},{"f":"track3/08-evaluating-retrieval.html","t":"Evaluating retrieval quality","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Why you must measure, and what to measure · Play with the metrics · RAG fails at retrieval or generation — measure them separate · A small golden set (queries → relevant chunks) unlocks real  · Recall@k = did we fetch it; precision@k = how clean the top- · Add faithfulness and answer correctness for end-to-end quali · The loop: change one knob → re-measure → keep or revert . Th · golden set · retrieval metrics · recall@k · precision@k · MRR · end-to-end metrics · LLM-as-judge","s":"This is the lesson that turns RAG from guesswork into engineering. Without measurement you’re tuning chunk sizes and rerankers by vibes. With it, every change is a number that went up or down — and you finally know whether you’re improving."},{"f":"track3/09-interview.html","t":"Interview check: RAG","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · The full RAG pipeline (index once; embed → retrieve → rerank · Chunking trade-offs and why overlap + metadata matter. · Same-model embedding rule; choosing a model empirically. · ANN recall/latency trade-off and metadata filtering as secur · Bi- vs cross-encoder, and reranking reorders but can’t fix r · Dense vs sparse vs hybrid, and RRF. · Grounding recipe, abstention, citation verification, faithfu · Evaluating retrieval vs generation separately, and the measu","s":"RAG is the most common system-design topic in applied-GenAI interviews, because it touches data, retrieval, prompting, and evaluation all at once. Here are the questions teams ask, the answers that signal seniority, and the debugging instincts they’re really probing for."},{"f":"track3/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: A question's journey through RAG","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Documents becoming points in a space , not keywords in an in · A question embedded by the same model , into the same space  · Retrieval as measuring distance — the whole mechanism, in on · The context window being assembled , and becoming the only t · An answer that can be traced to a source .","s":"RAG is usually drawn as boxes and arrows, which hides the one idea that matters: retrieval is geometry . Watch a question become a point in space, find its nearest neighbours, and come back with an answer it can prove."},{"f":"track3/lab.html","t":"Lab: Build a tiny RAG pipeline","tn":"RAG & Vector Databases","k":"3","x":"Step 1 — Chunk the documents · Step 2 — Turn text into vectors, and compare them · Step 3 — Retrieve the top-k · Step 4 — Ground the answer · Chunking — splitting documents into retrievable units. · Vectors + cosine similarity — the maths behind every embeddi · Top-k retrieval with a real relevance threshold. · A grounding prompt with citations and an explicit refusal pa","s":"Chunk, embed, retrieve, ground — the whole pipeline, written by you in plain Python, running in this page. No vector database, no API key. Once you’ve built it small, the production version is just the same shape with better parts."},{"f":"track4/01-chatbot-to-agent.html","t":"From chatbot to agent","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"Why agents exist · The autonomy spectrum · A chatbot answers; an agent accomplishes goals by calling to · An agent = LLM + tools + a decide-act-observe loop (+ option · Autonomy is a spectrum : plain LLM → tool-augmented → agent  · Use the least autonomy that solves the task — more autonomy  · The core shape: the model decides an action, your code execu · agent · tools · agent loop · Autonomy","s":"A chatbot answers what you ask. An agent accomplishes a goal — it can look things up, run calculations, call APIs, and take multiple steps, deciding what to do next based on what it sees. This is how LLMs move from “talks well” to “gets things done.”"},{"f":"track4/02-tool-calling.html","t":"Tool / function calling","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"The key idea: the model requests, your code executes · Step through the round-trip · Tool calling = the model emits a structured request ; your c · A tool schema (name + description + typed parameters) is wha · Tool descriptions are prompt surface — clear names and descr · Return the result as a tool-role message so the model can us · Prefer few, focused, well-described tools ; native tool-call · Tool calling · tool · tool schema · tool call · tool result","s":"This is the mechanism that makes agents possible: the model emits a structured request to call one of your functions, your code runs it, and the result goes back. Master this round-trip and you can connect an LLM to anything — calculators, APIs, databases, the whole outside world."},{"f":"track4/03-agent-loop.html","t":"The agent loop (ReAct)","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"Why a loop, and why interleave reasoning with acting · Watch an agent think · The agent loop repeats: the model picks an action, observes  · ReAct interleaves reasoning (thoughts) with acting (tool cal · Each step appends to the context — the model reasons over a  · The loop ends when the model emits a final answer or a guard · The loop is simple; the power is in good tools, clear prompt · ReAct · agent loop · step · stopping condition","s":"One tool call answers one question. Real tasks need several steps where each depends on the last. The agent loop — reason, act, observe, repeat — is the engine that turns a tool-using model into something that can actually solve problems."},{"f":"track4/04-planning.html","t":"Planning & decomposition","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"Why plan instead of just react · Three planning patterns · Planning decomposes a goal into ordered sub-tasks before exe · Plan-then-execute suits predictable tasks; plan-and-reflect  · An explicit plan gives you progress tracking, debuggability, · Don’t over-plan: simple tasks just need the reactive loop —  · The best agents combine planning (structure) with reactive e · Planning · Decomposition · Plan-then-execute · plan-and-reflect","s":"Reactive loops can wander on big goals — taking a step, then another, hoping to stumble toward done. Planning fixes that: break the goal into explicit sub-tasks first, then execute them. It makes long tasks more reliable, debuggable, and sometimes parallelizable."},{"f":"track4/05-memory.html","t":"Memory","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"Why memory is a real design problem · The two techniques you’ll actually use · Watch the model forget · Short-term memory = the context window (fast, limited); long · Summarize old turns to fit the window; store + retrieve fact · Long-term memory is RAG over the agent’s own history — the s · Distinguish episodic (past events) from semantic (distilled  · Memory is a deliberate write/read design , not something tha · Short-term memory · Long-term memory · episodic memory · semantic memory · user profile","s":"An agent that forgets everything between steps — or between sessions — can’t accomplish much. Memory is how an agent holds onto what it has learned, despite a small context window. And the good news: you already know the core trick. It’s RAG, pointed at the agent’s own history."},{"f":"track4/06-mcp.html","t":"MCP (Model Context Protocol)","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"The problem MCP solves · How it works in practice · MCP is an open standard for connecting AI apps to tools and  · A client (your agent) connects to servers that expose tools, · Build a connector once as an MCP server ; any MCP-compatible · It’s now industry-standard infrastructure (broad platform su · To the model, MCP tools look just like Lesson 4.2 tool calls · MCP · MCP host/client · MCP server · tools · resources · prompts","s":"Before MCP, every team wired up every tool by hand, in its own way. MCP is the standard plug that fixed it: build a tool or data connector once as an MCP server, and any MCP-compatible agent can use it. It’s become core industry infrastructure — worth understanding well."},{"f":"track4/07-multi-agent.html","t":"Multi-agent & orchestration","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"Why split one agent into several · The orchestration patterns · A router in action · Specialist agents with narrow roles + an orchestrator beat o · Common patterns: router, sequential pipeline, supervisor/hie · Benefits: modularity, simpler prompts, reliability, parallel · Costs: coordination overhead, more failure points, harder de · Single-agent first — add agents only when the task genuinely · specialist agents · orchestrator · multi-agent · specialist · handoff · orchestration pattern","s":"When one agent juggling a dozen tools and roles starts getting confused, the fix is often to split the work: focused specialist agents, coordinated by an orchestrator. Done right it’s cleaner and more reliable. Done reflexively it’s needless complexity — so we’ll be honest about when to reach for it."},{"f":"track4/08-failure-modes.html","t":"Failure modes & guards","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"Why guards aren’t optional · Try the guards · Every agent capability is also a failure mode — loops, bad a · Essential guards: step limit, arg validation, budgets/timeou · Use defense in depth — layer guards; don’t rely on any singl · Require human approval for irreversible/high-impact actions  · Log every step — observability is how you detect, debug, and · guard · step limit · argument validation · budgets & timeouts · human-in-the-loop · least privilege · observability · defense in depth","s":"An agent is software you’ve given autonomy and tools — which means it can fail in expensive, embarrassing, or dangerous ways no chatbot can. This lesson is the difference between a demo and something you’d actually let touch production: knowing the failure modes and guarding every one."},{"f":"track4/09-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Agents","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · Chatbot vs agent, and choosing the least autonomy that works · Tool calling end to end (schema → call → execute → result ba · The ReAct loop and why it needs a step limit; reading the tr · Planning (plan-then-execute vs reflect) and memory (short/lo · MCP: client/server, tools/resources/prompts, why it’s a stan · Multi-agent patterns and single-agent-first. · Failure modes and the full guard stack (code-level limits, H","s":"Agent questions test whether you can give a model autonomy responsibly — real tool use, a bounded loop, memory, and guards. Interviewers are listening for engineering maturity, not buzzwords. Here’s the set."},{"f":"track4/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: The agent loop, and how it runs away","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"Thought → action → observation , the cycle underneath every  · The model requesting a tool rather than running one — your c · Every fact in the answer traceable to an observation . · A runaway loop , and the budget that stops it.","s":"An agent is a loop with a budget. Watch a healthy one reason, call tools and stop — then run the same loop with a failing tool and see exactly where the money goes."},{"f":"track4/lab.html","t":"Lab: Build an agent loop","tn":"Agents & Tool Use","k":"4","x":"Step 1 — Give it tools · Step 2 — A planner that decides · Step 3 — Run the loop · Step 4 — Make it fail, then contain it · Tools with contracts and input validation. · A planner that chooses an action or finishes. · The ReAct loop — act, observe, decide again. · Guards : step caps and repeat-detection, so failure is bound","s":"An agent is a loop: think, act, observe, repeat. You’ll write real tools, a planner that decides which to call, the loop that runs them — and then the guards that stop it spinning forever, which is what separates a demo from something you’d let run unattended."},{"f":"track5/01-prompt-rag-finetune.html","t":"Prompt vs RAG vs fine-tune","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"Three ways to change what a model does · What fine-tuning is (and isn’t) for · Prompting & RAG change the input ; fine-tuning changes the w · RAG for knowledge, prompting for instructions, fine-tuning f · Fine-tune for consistent format/style/tone, narrow repeated  · Don’t fine-tune for fresh/changing facts (RAG) or one-offs ( · Fine-tuning and RAG often combine : behavior from fine-tunin · Fine-tuning · distillation","s":"Fine-tuning sounds like the “serious” option, so people reach for it first — and usually shouldn’t. Knowing exactly when fine-tuning is the right tool (and when prompting or RAG wins) is one of the clearest markers of an experienced GenAI engineer. Let’s build that judgment before we build a model."},{"f":"track5/02-how-training-works.html","t":"How training actually works","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"Training is just “guess, measure, adjust,” repeated · Roll the ball downhill · Training = predict → measure loss → nudge weights down the g · Fine-tuning is just more of this on your data, starting from · The learning rate controls step size: too small = slow; too  · Watch training vs. validation loss: if training keeps droppi · You don’t need the math — you need the loop, because it expl · weights · forward pass · loss · gradient · gradient descent · Backpropagation · learning rate · epoch · training set · validation set · early stopping","s":"Fine-tuning stops being mysterious once you see what “training” really is: a loop that nudges numbers downhill to make the model less wrong. You don’t need the calculus — you need the mental model, because it explains data, overfitting, and every knob you’ll touch."},{"f":"track5/03-data-preparation.html","t":"Data preparation","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"Why data is the whole game · The quality checklist · Data is the product of a fine-tune — the model mirrors your  · Use a consistent format (instruction→response / chat message · Quality & consistency beat quantity ; hundreds of clean pair · Dedupe, diversify, and prevent train/validation leakage. · Always keep a held-out validation set — it’s your only hones · training example · instruction → response · chat format · training set · validation set","s":"If fine-tuning fails, it’s almost always the data — not the algorithm. The dataset is the product of a fine-tune: the model becomes a mirror of the examples you show it. This lesson is how to build that mirror well."},{"f":"track5/04-lora-qlora.html","t":"LoRA & QLoRA","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"Why not just fine-tune the whole model? · Size a LoRA yourself · Full fine-tuning updates every weight — expensive; LoRA free · You train ~0.1–1% of parameters ; the adapter is a small (MB · QLoRA = 4-bit quantized base + LoRA → fine-tune a big model  · The base model is untouched , so you can serve many adapters · Rank r sets adapter capacity; start small (8–16), raise if u · LoRA · PEFT · rank · QLoRA · quantizes · adapter","s":"Full fine-tuning of a large model needs a small data center. LoRA and QLoRA are the breakthroughs that let you fine-tune on a single free GPU by training a tiny add-on instead of the whole model. This is how fine-tuning is actually done today — and you can run it for free."},{"f":"track5/05-instruction-tuning.html","t":"Instruction tuning","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"From “continues text” to “follows instructions” · Instruction tuning (SFT) trains on instruction→response pair · It’s how base models become assistants , and how you special · Preference tuning (RLHF/DPO) aligns the model with human pre · Always use the correct chat template , and train in the exac · After SFT, the taught behavior is baked in — no need to repe · Instruction tuning · Supervised fine-tuning · chat template · Preference tuning · RLHF · DPO","s":"This is the most common kind of fine-tuning, and the one that turned raw next-token predictors into the helpful assistants you use every day. Understand it and you understand both how to specialize a model and how ChatGPT-style models are actually made."},{"f":"track5/06-evaluating-finetune.html","t":"Evaluating a fine-tune","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"Two questions every fine-tune must answer · Always compare to the base model on a held-out set — “feels  · Measure the target task (should rise) and general ability (s · Watch for overfitting (train ≫ held-out) and catastrophic fo · If general ability drops: fewer epochs, more/diverse data, l · Evaluation is what turns fine-tuning from a gamble into engi · catastrophic forgetting · baseline · held-out set · task metric · general-ability · overfitting · regression / catastrophic forgetting","s":"A fine-tune that feels better is worthless; you need proof. And the dangerous failure isn’t obvious badness — it’s a model that aced your task while quietly getting worse at everything else. This lesson is how to know, with numbers, whether you actually improved things."},{"f":"track5/07-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Fine-tuning","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · Prompt vs RAG vs fine-tune, and the “try in that order” rule · What training does (predict → loss → gradient step) and over · Data quality, format-matches-inference, and leakage. · LoRA and QLoRA — what each contributes, and adapter serving. · SFT vs RLHF/DPO, and the chat-template gotcha. · Evaluating vs the base on held-out data; catastrophic forget","s":"Fine-tuning questions test judgment more than mechanics: do you know when to fine-tune, and can you do it cheaply and prove it worked? Interviewers love this topic because it separates people who reach for fine-tuning reflexively from those who reach for it wisely."},{"f":"track5/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: What fine-tuning actually changes","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"Full fine-tuning touching every weight — and what that costs · The base model frozen , so pretrained knowledge cannot be da · Small adapter matrices added beside each layer, sized by ran · Gradients flowing into under 1% of the parameters. · A deployable artefact measured in megabytes .","s":"“Fine-tuning” sounds like retraining the model. It isn’t — and LoRA barely touches it at all. Watch which weights move, which stay frozen, and why that difference is what put fine-tuning on a free GPU."},{"f":"track5/lab.html","t":"Lab: Prepare data & size a LoRA","tn":"Fine-tuning & Adapters","k":"5","x":"Step 1 — Build the dataset · Step 2 — Quality checks that decide the outcome · Step 3 — Why LoRA is cheap (the actual numbers) · Step 4 — Should you fine-tune at all? · An instruction dataset in the shape trainers expect. · Quality gates — dedupe and length checks that decide success · The LoRA parameter maths , in real numbers. · A decision function that tells you when not to fine-tune.","s":"Fine-tuning is 90% data work and a little arithmetic. You’ll build a training dataset, run the quality checks that decide whether the tune succeeds, compute exactly how few parameters LoRA trains — and write the decision function that tells you whether to fine-tune at all."},{"f":"track6/01-why-evals.html","t":"Why evals decide everything","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"The problem: you can’t improve what you can’t measure · LLM outputs are open-ended, so without evals every change is · An eval needs a golden set , a metric , and a baseline to co · The loop: change → score → compare → keep or revert . Improv · Evals catch silent regressions you’d never spot by eyeballin · You can start with a 12-line harness — having any eval beats · Evals · eval · golden set · metric · baseline","s":"Every track so far ended with the same word: measure it . This is the track that makes measuring a first-class skill. Evals are the single biggest thing separating people who demo LLM features from people who ship reliable ones — and most teams underinvest here badly."},{"f":"track6/02-golden-sets.html","t":"Golden sets","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"Why the golden set is the foundation · How to build one (it’s less work than you fear) · A golden set = representative inputs + known-good answers/cr · Build from real inputs , include edge cases & failures , cov · Keep it held out (don’t overfit to it) and living (grow it w · Small & representative beats large & random — 30–50 sharp ca · Score per category to localize regressions, not just a singl · golden set · representative · edge cases · held out · living","s":"An eval is only as good as the examples it runs on. The golden set is that foundation — a curated set of inputs with known-good answers that becomes your team’s shared definition of “working.” Build it well and everything downstream gets trustworthy."},{"f":"track6/03-llm-as-judge.html","t":"LLM-as-judge","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"Why we need a model to grade models · Judge an answer yourself · LLM-as-judge scores open-ended outputs where exact-match fai · Give it a clear rubric (and a reference when you have one);  · Pairwise (“which is better?”) is often more reliable than ab · Judges have biases (verbosity, position, self-preference) —  · Use code metrics for closed outputs, the judge for fuzzy qua · LLM-as-judge · rubric · Reference-based · reference-free · Pointwise · pairwise · validate","s":"How do you score “is this answer helpful, faithful, and well-written?” at scale, when there’s no single right string? You use a model to grade the output. It’s the workhorse of modern evals — powerful, scalable, and full of pitfalls you must know about."},{"f":"track6/04-offline-online.html","t":"Offline vs online evals","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"Two complementary measurements · What online signals look like · Offline (golden set) is fast, cheap, repeatable — use it to  · Online (A/B, feedback, outcomes) is the ground truth — use i · Offline is a proxy ; the offline–online gap is where surpris · Watch guardrail metrics (latency, cost, errors) alongside qu · Feed online failures back into the golden set so offline get · offline eval · Online eval · Offline evaluation · Online evaluation · A/B test · user feedback · outcome metrics","s":"Your golden set tells you a change is good before you ship. Real users tell you if it’s actually good after you ship. Mature teams use both — and know the gap between them is where surprises live."},{"f":"track6/05-tracing-observability.html","t":"Tracing & observability","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"Why LLM systems are hard to debug without tracing · What to capture per request · LLM features are multi-step and non-deterministic — the fina · A trace records one request as timed spans (retrieve, prompt · Capture the exact prompt and retrieved context — that’s what · Monitor & alert on latency, cost, and error rates to catch p · Start with plain logging ; free tools (Langfuse, Phoenix) ad · Observability · tracing · trace · span · Monitoring · alerts · online evals at scale","s":"When a RAG pipeline or agent gives a bad answer in production, “the model messed up” isn’t a diagnosis. Tracing gives you an X-ray of every request — what was retrieved, what prompt was sent, what each step cost — so you can actually find and fix the problem."},{"f":"track6/06-regression-testing.html","t":"Regression-testing prompts","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"Why prompts need tests like code does · Run the gate · Prompts/models/RAG are changeable behavior that silently reg · An eval suite run in CI turns your golden set into a pass/fa · Define the gate explicitly: no case may regress , or overall · Keep LLM tests non-flaky with temperature 0 and structural / · Version prompts so you can compare and roll back. · regression test · eval suite · gate · Prompt versioning","s":"A “tiny” prompt tweak to fix one case can silently break five others — and you won’t notice until a user does. The fix is to treat prompts like code: a test suite that runs on every change and blocks regressions. This is where evals become a habit, not an afterthought."},{"f":"track6/07-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Evals","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · Why evals matter, and the change → score → compare loop. · Building a golden set (real inputs, edge cases, living, per- · LLM-as-judge: rubric, pairwise, biases, validate against hum · Offline vs online; the staged rollout; guardrail metrics. · Tracing/spans for debugging, and PII in logs. · Regression testing as CI; keeping LLM tests non-flaky. · Evaluating RAG (retrieval vs generation) and agents end to e","s":"This is the topic that most reveals seniority. Anyone can build a demo; only people who measure can ship and improve. Interviewers probe hard here — they want to hear a measurement mindset, not prompt-tinkering."},{"f":"track6/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: Watch an eval gate catch a regression","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"A golden set as the fixed yardstick for every change. · An average that looks fine while specific cases regress. · A per-case gate blocking the merge, refusal included.","s":"The scariest bug in an LLM product is the one that passes review. Watch a harmless-looking prompt change sail past the average score — and get caught by a per-case gate that's watching the two things that actually broke."},{"f":"track6/lab.html","t":"Lab: Build an eval harness","tn":"Evals & Observability","k":"6","x":"Step 1 — Write a golden set · Step 2 — Score an answer · Step 3 — Evaluate two versions · Step 4 — Gate the deploy · A golden set including a refusal case. · An automatic scorer . · An A/B evaluation across two versions. · A quality gate that blocks a regression — the core of eval-d · golden set","s":"This is the skill that separates people who ship AI from people who demo it. You’ll build a golden set, a scorer, and a quality gate — then watch a “friendlier” new version get blocked because your harness caught the damage it did."},{"f":"track7/01-threat-model.html","t":"The threat model","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"Why LLM apps need a fresh threat model · The main LLM-specific threats · LLM apps blur the code/data line — the model treats all text · Draw the trust boundary : user input, retrieved docs, and to · Outputs are risky too — they can leak data or trigger harmfu · The core LLM threats: injection, jailbreaks, PII leakage, un · Threat-model before building: list assets, untrusted inputs, · trust boundary · threat model · assets · untrusted inputs · attacker goals · red-teaming","s":"Before you can defend an LLM app, you have to know what you’re defending against. LLM systems have a genuinely new attack surface — they take instructions in natural language and act on text from untrusted sources. This lesson is the map of what can go wrong, so the next lessons can fix each piece."},{"f":"track7/02-prompt-injection.html","t":"Prompt injection","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"Why it happens · See it, and see a defense · Prompt injection = untrusted text carrying instructions that · Direct (user message) vs indirect (hidden in retrieved docs  · Prompt-level defenses help: fence untrusted text as data and · But it’s not fully solvable — never rely on prompt wording f · Real protection is structural : least privilege, human appro · prompt injection · Prompt injection · Direct injection · Indirect injection","s":"This is the defining vulnerability of LLM apps and the one interviewers probe hardest. The model can’t tell your instructions from instructions hidden in the text it’s processing — so attacker-controlled text can hijack your app. You can’t fully eliminate it, but you can contain it."},{"f":"track7/03-jailbreaks.html","t":"Jailbreaks","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"Jailbreak vs. injection · The defense stack · A jailbreak bypasses the model’s safety training; injection  · Families: role-play, override, obfuscation, multi-turn escal · No defense is perfect — it’s an arms race ; assume some atte · Layer: safety-trained model + system prompt + input/output m · Decode/normalize text before moderating, and re-check every  · Prompt injection · jailbreak · role-play · override · obfuscation · multi-turn escalation · arms race","s":"A jailbreak tricks the model into bypassing its own safety training to produce content it’s supposed to refuse. If your app is public-facing, people will try. You can’t make it impossible, but you can make it hard, detectable, and low-impact."},{"f":"track7/04-pii-privacy.html","t":"PII & privacy","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"Why privacy is a first-class concern here · Try a redactor · LLM apps leak PII via heavy logging, third-party API calls,  · Redact PII before logging, before sending to third parties,  · Practice data minimization and retention limits — don’t coll · Regex catches structured PII; use a model-based detector (e. · Privacy is a legal duty (GDPR, etc.), not optional hygiene — · PII · Redaction · Data minimization · Retention limits","s":"LLM apps swim in user data — and they log it, send it to third-party models, and sometimes repeat it back. Mishandling personal information isn’t just bad hygiene; it’s a legal liability. This lesson is how to handle data responsibly without crippling your app."},{"f":"track7/05-content-safety.html","t":"Content safety","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"Why moderate both sides · Moderate input and output with independent classifiers — two · The output gate is the backstop for content the model produc · Use purpose-built safety models (free Llama Guard , hosted m · Moderation is a precision/recall trade-off ; calibrate thres · Normalize/decode text before moderating to defeat obfuscatio · Content moderation · Input moderation · output moderation · Llama Guard","s":"Even a well-behaved model can be pushed into producing harmful content, and a public app that does so under your brand is a serious problem. Content moderation is the independent safety net: classifiers that check what comes in and what goes out, separate from the model itself."},{"f":"track7/06-output-validation.html","t":"Output validation","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"Why output is an attack surface · Model output is untrusted — it’s shaped by attacker-influenc · Validate before use: parse the schema, allowlist values/acti · Insecure output handling (XSS, SQL injection, unsafe actions · Enforce hard limits and allowed actions in code , never via  · This closes the loop: untrusted in and untrusted out. · XSS · Output validation · schema validation · sanitization · allowlisting · leak checks","s":"The model’s output is not trusted code — it’s text generated from (possibly poisoned) inputs. The moment you feed it into HTML, a database query, a shell, or an action, it becomes an attack vector. Validating output before use closes the loop on LLM security."},{"f":"track7/07-defense-in-depth.html","t":"Defense in depth","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"Why one layer is never enough · Every single guard is imperfect — layer independent defenses · The stack: input moderation → prompt hardening → least-privi · Least privilege is the most powerful layer: a hijacked model · Assume each layer leaks; design so the blast radius is conta · Match the depth to the risk — an internal tool needs less th · Defense in depth · least privilege · input moderation · prompt hardening · least-privilege tools · human-in-the-loop · output validation · monitoring · Least privilege","s":"Every guard in this track is imperfect on its own — moderation misses things, prompts get injected, models get jailbroken. The whole strategy is to layer them so that no single failure becomes a breach. This lesson assembles the pieces into a coherent defense."},{"f":"track7/08-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Safety","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · The LLM threat model and trust boundary (input and output un · Prompt injection (direct/indirect) and why it’s not fully so · Jailbreak vs injection; per-turn moderation; the arms race. · PII redaction at the three boundaries; minimization; the thi · Content moderation on both sides; using a separate safety mo · Output validation / insecure output handling (XSS, SQL, acti · Defense in depth + least privilege, and matching depth to ri","s":"Safety questions reveal whether you’d actually let your system near real users. Interviewers want a security mindset: you assume the model can be manipulated and you build trustworthy guards around it. Here’s the set."},{"f":"track7/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: Watch an attack meet your defences","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"An injection arriving as ordinary retrieved data . · Layers that work by persuading the model — and their limits. · Layers that hold structurally , whatever the model decides. · The real security question: what survives everything .","s":"There is no prompt that makes a system safe. There are only layers, each one imperfect. Watch a real injection payload travel through five of them — then switch layers off and find out which ones were actually doing the work."},{"f":"track7/lab.html","t":"Lab: Break a bot, then build the guard","tn":"Guardrails & Safety","k":"7","x":"Step 1 — Watch the hijack · Step 2 — Detect the obvious attempts · Step 3 — Build the layered defence · Step 4 — Attack your own guard · A working prompt-injection attack — so you know it firsthand · A pattern detector as a cheap first layer. · A fenced, guarded prompt that separates data from instructio · An adversarial test suite that proved your own defence incom","s":"First you’ll hijack a support bot with a single poisoned sentence hidden in a document. Then you’ll build the layered defence that stops it — and run a suite of attacks against your own guard to see exactly what it catches and what it doesn’t."},{"f":"track8/01-cost-latency-model.html","t":"The cost & latency model","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Cost and latency are both about tokens · Estimate your bill · Cost ≈ (input + output tokens) × price ; input and output ar · Latency ≈ TTFT (prefill) + output tokens × time-per-token (d · Output tokens are the expensive ones — on both cost and late · A long prompt raises TTFT/input cost; a long answer raises d · Estimate cost from token counts before launch — and watch ho · Latency · prefill · time to first token · decode","s":"A feature that works in a demo can be unaffordable or unbearably slow at scale. To ship for real, you need a mental model of where the dollars and the milliseconds actually go. Both come down to one thing you already understand: tokens."},{"f":"track8/02-streaming.html","t":"Streaming","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Perceived latency is what users feel · Feel the difference · Streaming shows tokens as they’re generated — same total tim · TTFT (time to first token) is the number users actually feel · It’s usually a single flag ( stream=True ) plus pushing chun · It doesn’t reduce cost or total time — it improves the felt  · Default to streaming for chat ; don’t stream when you need t · streaming · perceived latency · Streaming · Time to first token · Perceived latency","s":"The cheapest, highest-impact latency improvement doesn’t make the model faster at all — it just shows the user the words as they’re generated. Streaming is the difference between a chat that feels instant and one that feels broken, and it’s a few lines of code."},{"f":"track8/03-caching.html","t":"Caching","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Why caching is so effective here · What a cache is worth · The cheapest call is one you skip — caching turns repeats in · Exact cache (identical prompt), semantic cache (similar via  · Because LLM calls cost far more than a lookup, even a modest · The semantic threshold is a correctness knob — too loose ser · Don’t cache personalized, time-sensitive, or intentionally-v · Caching · exact cache · semantic cache · Prompt/prefix caching · hit rate","s":"The fastest, cheapest LLM call is the one you never make. Many production workloads ask the same or similar things over and over — and caching turns those repeats into instant, near-free responses. It’s often the single biggest cost win available."},{"f":"track8/04-model-routing.html","t":"Model routing","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Not every query needs your best model · Route by task, not by habit · Models vary hugely in cost/speed; most queries are easy — do · Routing sends each query to the cheapest model that can hand · A cascade tries cheap first and escalates only on low confid · This moves you along the cost/quality frontier — most of the · Measure the escalation rate and small-path quality; tune the · Model routing · router · cascade · cost/quality frontier","s":"Using your most powerful model for every request is like taking a helicopter to the corner store. Most queries are easy; routing them to a small, cheap model — and reserving the big one for hard cases — can cut costs dramatically with little quality loss."},{"f":"track8/05-quantization.html","t":"Quantization","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Smaller numbers, smaller model · Trade precision for memory · Quantization stores weights with fewer bits (16 → 8 → 4), sh · Result: less memory, faster, cheaper hardware — with a usual · 8-bit is often near-lossless; 4-bit is the popular sweet spo · It’s the default that makes free local models (Ollama/GGUF)  · When self-hosting, the quant level is a key cost/quality dia · Quantization · precision · Ollama · GGUF","s":"Quantization shrinks a model by storing its weights with fewer bits — making it smaller, faster, and runnable on cheaper hardware, with usually only a small quality cost. It’s why you can run capable models on a laptop (the free local stack of this whole course), and a key lever when you self-host."},{"f":"track8/06-batching-throughput.html","t":"Batching & throughput","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Why GPUs love batches · Throughput against latency · A GPU serving one request is mostly idle; batching runs many · Batching raises throughput (requests/sec per GPU) → lower co · Throughput vs latency is a trade-off : bigger batches serve  · Continuous batching (vLLM, TGI) adds/removes requests dynami · The serving engine handles it — you configure and reason abo · Batching · throughput · Throughput · latency · Continuous batching · vLLM","s":"A GPU running one request at a time is mostly idle. Batching processes many requests together to keep it busy, dramatically increasing how many users one machine can serve. It’s the key to serving LLMs affordably at scale — and the source of the latency-vs-throughput trade-off you’ll constantly balance."},{"f":"track8/07-budgeting-tokens.html","t":"Budgeting tokens","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Every token is paid, every time · Every token is paid on every call — prompt size is a per-req · Account for where tokens go (system, examples, history, cont · Levers: shorter system prompt, fewer examples (or fine-tune  · Output tokens are doubly costly (price + decode latency) — c · Measure first — don’t trim the part that isn’t the problem. · Token budgeting · token budget · max output tokens","s":"Caching skips calls, routing right-sizes them, batching speeds the hardware — but every call you do make still spends tokens, on every request, forever. Token budgeting is the most universal lever: make each prompt as lean as it can be, and you pay less on literally every call."},{"f":"track8/08-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Serving","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · The token-driven cost & latency model (prefill/TTFT vs decod · Streaming and perceived latency (and when not to stream). · Caching (exact / semantic / prefix) and its correctness risk · Model routing and cascades; the cost/quality frontier. · Quantization (bits → memory/speed/quality) and when it appli · Batching/throughput and the latency trade-off (self-hosting) · Token budgeting: measure where tokens go, trim the biggest.","s":"Serving questions test whether you can take a working LLM feature and make it affordable and fast at scale. Interviewers want a clear cost/latency model and the right lever for each bottleneck. Here’s the set."},{"f":"track8/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: Watch tokens become time and money","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Prefill — the whole input read in one parallel pass. · Decode — the reply generated one serial token at a time. · Why output dominates cost and latency, and how streaming hid","s":"Every architecture argument about cost and latency comes down to one asymmetry: input is read all at once, output is written one token at a time. Watch a single request move through both, and see where the seconds and the cents actually go."},{"f":"track8/lab.html","t":"Lab: Build a cost & latency calculator","tn":"Serving, Latency & Cost","k":"8","x":"Step 1 — Tokens to dollars · Step 2 — Scale it to a real workload · Step 3 — Pull the levers · Step 4 — Latency, and what streaming really does · A cost model : tokens → dollars, input vs output priced sepa · A workload projection that turns fractions of a cent into a  · A lever simulator : routing, caching, trimming — stacked. · A latency model separating time-to-first-token from decode t","s":"Every serving decision is arithmetic you can do yourself. Build the model that turns tokens into dollars and seconds, then pull the four real levers — routing, caching, trimming, streaming — and watch a scary bill become a small one."},{"f":"track13/01-why-text-to-sql.html","t":"Why text-to-SQL (and where it breaks)","tn":"Structured Data & Text-to-SQL","k":"9","x":"The problem it kills · What it looks like · Where it breaks (be honest in interviews) · Text-to-SQL = English question → generated SQL → safe run →  · It’s one of the highest-demand GenAI applications, and the h · Correctness hinges on the model understanding the schema , n · Failure modes: ambiguity, schema misunderstanding, wrong-but · The dangerous failure is a confident wrong number — which is · Text-to-SQL","s":"Most of the world’s valuable data lives in databases, and most of the people who need answers can’t write SQL. Text-to-SQL closes that gap — and it’s the single most natural place for a data engineer to shine in GenAI. This lesson frames the problem, the payoff, and the honest failure modes."},{"f":"track13/02-schema-aware-prompting.html","t":"Schema-aware prompting","tn":"Structured Data & Text-to-SQL","k":"9","x":"Why the schema is the prompt · Show, don’t just tell: few-shot examples · When there are 400 tables: select, don’t dump · The schema is the prompt : give exact tables, columns, types · Add instructions that constrain: “use ONLY these columns,” “ · Few-shot Q→SQL examples teach your conventions (how “revenue · With many tables, retrieve the relevant few (schema RAG) ins · Sample rows prevent value mistakes ( 'Canada' vs 'CA' , 'pai · example pairs","s":"A text-to-SQL model is only as good as its picture of your database. This lesson is about feeding it the right context — the schema, descriptions, and a few examples — and, when you have hundreds of tables, giving it just the slice it needs."},{"f":"track13/03-safe-sql.html","t":"Generating safe, correct SQL","tn":"Structured Data & Text-to-SQL","k":"9","x":"Why you never trust generated SQL · The layers, strongest first · Never trust generated SQL — and never make the prompt your o · The bedrock control is a read-only database user : writes be · Add layers: validate SELECT-only & single-statement , force  · Defense in depth: assume any one layer can fail, so keep sev · This is Track 7’s security mindset applied to databases.","s":"You are about to let a language model write queries that run against your database. That sentence should make you nervous — and this lesson turns that nervousness into layered, boring, reliable safety."},{"f":"track13/04-self-correcting-agent.html","t":"The self-correcting SQL agent","tn":"Structured Data & Text-to-SQL","k":"9","x":"Why a single shot isn’t enough · The loop, with guards · Beyond errors: verify the result, and ask when unsure · First-try SQL often fails; feeding the database’s error mess · This is the ReAct agent loop (Track 4): act (run) → observe  · Bound the retries (2–3) and fail gracefully — the safe read- · Return the SQL with the answer for transparency and auditing · Handle wrong-but-runs by checking result shape, and handle a · agent loop","s":"First tries fail: a wrong column name, a bad join, a dialect quirk. The trick that makes text-to-SQL feel reliable is letting the system read its own error and fix itself — the agent loop from Track 4, pointed at a database."},{"f":"track13/05-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Data & SQL agents","tn":"Structured Data & Text-to-SQL","k":"9","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · The end-to-end pipeline: schema prompt → SQL → safe run → an · Why the read-only user is the bedrock safety control, and th · Scaling with schema retrieval and a semantic layer . · Execution accuracy on a golden set — comparing results, not  · The self-correction loop , bounded retries, and asking when  · When to constrain or not ship open-ended SQL by how costly a","s":"Text-to-SQL is a favorite interview topic precisely because it exposes whether you think about safety, scale, and correctness — not just prompting. It’s also where your data background lets you outshine everyone. Here are the questions teams ask, with strong answers."},{"f":"track13/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: Watch a question become safe SQL","tn":"Structured Data & Text-to-SQL","k":"9","x":"Schema grounding — the model needs the real tables and colum · Generated SQL that looks right , which is exactly what you m · A safety gate in code — allowlist, read-only, single stateme · The same gate rejecting a destructive request the model prop","s":"Text-to-SQL is the highest-leverage GenAI skill for a data engineer — and the one where a wrong move costs the most. Watch a plain-English question become a query, pass a safety gate, and run; then watch a destructive request meet the same gate."},{"f":"track13/lab.html","t":"Lab: Build a safe text-to-SQL runner","tn":"Structured Data & Text-to-SQL","k":"9","x":"Step 1 — Stand up a real database · Step 2 — Write the guard · Step 3 — Answer real questions · Step 4 — Try to break it · A real database running locally, seeded and queried. · A validator enforcing single-statement, read-only SQL. · A safe execution path with bounded results. · A live attack test proving the guard holds.","s":"This is the one that plays to your decade of data work. You’ll spin up a real SQLite database in this page , write the safety layer that stands between a language model and your data, then try to break it — and watch it hold."},{"f":"track15/01-vision-language-models.html","t":"Beyond text: vision-language models","tn":"Multimodal AI","k":"10","x":"What a vision-language model is · What it looks like (free and local) · Where VLMs break · A vision-language model (VLM) takes images + text and reason · Images become tokens: split into patches → vision encoder →  · Uses: description, visual Q&A , reading text, chart/diagram  · Free/local is possible — open VLMs like LLaVA via Ollama ; t · Weaknesses: precise spatial reasoning, counting, small text, · vision-language model · patches · vision encoder · visual question answering","s":"Everything so far has been words in, words out. But a huge amount of the world’s information is visual — screenshots, receipts, charts, product photos, scanned forms. Vision-language models let a system see , and that unlocks a whole class of products."},{"f":"track15/02-document-ai-ocr.html","t":"Document AI & OCR","tn":"Multimodal AI","k":"10","x":"The problem: documents aren’t data · The old way vs the new way · Best of both: OCR + VLM · Document AI = image of a document → clean structured fields; · OCR (e.g. free Tesseract) transcribes the text but not its m · VLMs read text and layout, extracting fields with no per-ven · Validate the JSON against a schema (pydantic) so bad extract · For critical fields, combine OCR + VLM and flag disagreement · Document AI · OCR","s":"Turning documents into structured data — invoices, forms, receipts, contracts — is the highest-value multimodal use case in business, and one VLMs changed overnight. This lesson covers OCR, the new VLM-based approach, and how to make extraction trustworthy."},{"f":"track15/03-audio.html","t":"Audio: speech-to-text & TTS","tn":"Multimodal AI","k":"10","x":"The two halves of audio AI · The voice-app pipeline · What makes voice hard · Speech-to-text (Whisper — free/open) makes transcripts; text · Voice apps are a pipeline: audio → STT → LLM → TTS → audio ; · Big, easy wins: meeting notes, call analytics, voice assista · Transcription errors propagate downstream; accents, noise, a · Real-time latency is hard (three models in series) — stream  · Speech-to-text · Text-to-speech","s":"Voice is how people most naturally communicate, and it’s now cheap to work with. This lesson covers turning speech into text, text into speech, and how they combine with an LLM to build voice applications — meeting notes, assistants, call analytics."},{"f":"track15/04-multimodal-rag.html","t":"Multimodal RAG","tn":"Multimodal AI","k":"10","x":"Why retrieve over images · Two ways to make images searchable · Then ground with a VLM · Multimodal RAG widens “documents” to images (photos, charts, · Make images searchable two ways: shared-space embeddings (CL · CLIP puts images and text in one vector space , so a text qu · Ground the answer by feeding retrieved images to a VLM , and · All free/open: CLIP via sentence-transformers , a VLM via Ol · Multimodal RAG · CLIP","s":"RAG gave a model your documents. Multimodal RAG gives it your images too — product photos, charts, diagrams, scanned pages — so it can retrieve and reason over visual knowledge, not just text. It’s Track 3 with a wider definition of “document.”"},{"f":"track15/05-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Multimodal","tn":"Multimodal AI","k":"10","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · How an image becomes tokens (patches → vectors → tokens) and · Document AI : VLM + structured output + validation, and OCR  · Why irreversible high-stakes actions need verification and h · The voice pipeline (STT → LLM → TTS) and why transcription e · Multimodal RAG : CLIP shared-space vs caption-then-embed, an · Cost/latency of vision, and carrying evaluation discipline i","s":"Multimodal questions test whether you can recognize when a problem is really a vision or audio problem, pick the right tool, and apply your existing discipline to richer inputs. Here’s what teams ask, with strong answers."},{"f":"track15/visual-lab.html","t":"Visual Lab: Watch a document become data","tn":"Multimodal AI","k":"10","x":"A document as pixels , then read into messy text. · Structured field extraction the model returns confidently, r · Validation — the date trap and plausible-range checks. · An independent cross-check and risk-based routing to a human","s":"Turning a scanned invoice into database rows is the highest-value multimodal task in business — and the easiest to get dangerously wrong. Watch the read, and then watch the four stages that exist only to stop a confident wrong number reaching your accounts."},{"f":"track15/lab.html","t":"Lab: Document extraction you can trust","tn":"Multimodal AI","k":"10","x":"Step 1 — The document as text · Step 2 — Extract the fields · Step 3 — Validate and normalise · Step 4 — Cross-check, then decide who sees it · Field extraction from realistic, messy document text. · Validation and normalisation , including the date trap. · An independent cross-check against line items. · Risk-based routing — auto-approve, review, or require a huma","s":"Turning a scanned invoice into database rows is the highest-value multimodal task in business — and the easiest to get dangerously wrong. You’ll extract the fields, validate them, cross-check the arithmetic, and build the routing rule that decides what a human must see."},{"f":"track12/01-advanced-rag.html","t":"Advanced RAG","tn":"Going Deeper","k":"11","x":"Why basic RAG plateaus · 1 · Fix the query before you search · 2 · Retrieve broadly, then rerank precisely · 3 · Curate the context window · 4 · Measure it like an engineer · Advanced RAG = targeted fixes for specific failures, each me · Query transformation (rewrite, multi-query, decomposition, H · Retrieve broadly (bi-encoder) then rerank (cross-encoder) fo · Curate context : order strongest first/last (“lost in the mi · Measure four things — context recall, context precision, fai · Query transformation · bi-encoder · cross-encoder reranker · “lost in the middle” · approximate nearest neighbor","s":"Track 3 got you a working, grounded RAG system. This lesson covers what you reach for when “embed and take the top k” isn’t good enough — query transformation, reranking, context curation, and the rigorous evaluation that tells you which change actually helped."},{"f":"track12/02-advanced-agents.html","t":"Advanced agents","tn":"Going Deeper","k":"11","x":"Why agents are hard to trust · The reliability toolkit · Evaluate the journey, not just the destination · Agents compound per-step error; advanced work is engineering · Reflection catches errors before finishing; plan-then-execut · Validate tool results — models build confidently on garbage. · Evaluate the trajectory (tool choice, arg quality, recovery) · Tracing every step makes agents observable — you can’t debug · trajectory","s":"Track 4 built an agent that calls tools and loops. This lesson is about making one reliable — the patterns that turn an impressive demo into something you’d trust to run unattended, and how to evaluate whether it actually works."},{"f":"track12/03-advanced-evals.html","t":"Advanced evals","tn":"Going Deeper","k":"11","x":"Why your eval needs its own eval · 1 · Calibrate the judge against humans · 2 · Cancel the biases you can predict · 3 · Respect the noise · An unvalidated judge is an unvalidated model — calibrate it  · Judges have systematic biases (position, verbosity, self-pre · Swap positions and average , and prefer pairwise over absolu · Respect run-to-run noise : fix the seed/temp 0, use enough e · Rigor in the measurement is what lets evals safely drive dec · agreement · Cohen’s κ","s":"Track 6 made you measure. This lesson makes your measurements trustworthy — calibrating LLM judges, cancelling their biases, and using enough statistical care that “v2 is better” is a fact, not a hopeful glance at a number that ticked up."},{"f":"track12/lab.html","t":"Lab: Advanced retrieval, measured","tn":"Going Deeper","k":"11","x":"Step 1 — Watch baseline retrieval miss · Step 2 — Expand the query, then fuse the rankings · Step 3 — Rerank the shortlist · Step 4 — Prove it with recall@k · A reproduction of the vocabulary-mismatch failure — the one  · Query expansion + reciprocal rank fusion . · A rerank stage over a cheap shortlist. · recall@k measured before and after — evidence, not opinion.","s":"Basic retrieval fails on a question you’ll meet constantly: the user’s words don’t match the document’s. You’ll watch it fail, fix it with query expansion and rank fusion, add a reranker — and then prove the improvement with recall@k instead of claiming it."},{"f":"track14/01-notebook-to-service.html","t":"From notebook to a service","tn":"Productionization & LLMOps","k":"12","x":"Why an API is the unlock · A model service in ~15 lines · A web service (API) lets other software use your model logic · FastAPI wraps your code in endpoints (e.g. POST /ask ) in a  · pydantic models validate requests automatically (clear error · The endpoint body is just your existing logic — productioniz · It stays free/local with Ollama; no keys or bills to stand i · web service","s":"A model call in a notebook helps exactly one person: you. To let anyone — a website, an app, a teammate — use it, you wrap it in a small web service. This lesson turns your working code into an API others can call."},{"f":"track14/02-packaging-deploy.html","t":"Packaging & deploy","tn":"Productionization & LLMOps","k":"12","x":"Why containers: kill “works on my machine” · Config and secrets: never bake them in · Where to deploy (free options) · Containers (Docker) package code + its whole environment so  · A Dockerfile is the recipe; pinned requirements.txt versions · Config from environment variables , never hardcoded — same i · Secrets never go in code or git. Use env vars / secret manag · Deploy a container to a free host ( Render / Railway / Fly.i · container · environment variables","s":"“It works on my machine” is not a deployment strategy. Containers make your service run the same everywhere, and a little discipline with config and secrets keeps it safe. This lesson gets your API off your laptop."},{"f":"track14/03-ci-evals.html","t":"CI for prompts & evals","tn":"Productionization & LLMOps","k":"12","x":"Why LLM apps need an eval gate · What runs in CI · LLM regressions are silent — no error, just worse output — s · Add an eval gate : CI runs your golden set and blocks the ch · Run deterministic tests (temp 0: valid JSON, right retrieval · The mechanism is a non-zero exit code on a failing eval — th · Prompts live in version control , so every prompt change is  · CI · eval gate","s":"In normal software, tests in CI stop you shipping bugs. In LLM software, a one-word prompt tweak can quietly wreck quality with no error anywhere. The fix is the same idea, upgraded: make every change pass your evals before it can ship."},{"f":"track14/04-monitoring.html","t":"Monitoring in production","tn":"Productionization & LLMOps","k":"12","x":"Why monitoring is non-negotiable · What to watch · The loop that makes it worth it · Watch an incident hide inside the average · Golden sets test the anticipated; production reveals the una · Watch four things: traces , cost & latency , quality signals · Traces let you debug a specific bad answer by seeing retriev · Close the loop: production failures become new golden-set ca · A monitored, feedback-wired system gets more reliable over t · drift · online evals","s":"Your evals test what you thought of. Real users do what you didn’t. Monitoring is how you see the truth of your system in the wild — and turn its failures into the next round of improvements."},{"f":"track14/05-interview.html","t":"Interview check: LLMOps","tn":"Productionization & LLMOps","k":"12","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · Notebook → FastAPI service → Docker → deployed URL. · Why containers give reproducibility; config & secrets from t · The eval gate in CI (non-zero exit blocks deploy) and why LL · Monitoring: traces, cost/latency, quality signals ; offline  · The feedback loop : production failures become golden-set ca · Stateless services & external state for chat memory at scale","s":"“Can you take this prototype to production?” is the question that separates a hobbyist from a hire. This track is your answer. Here’s how teams probe it, with strong responses — and another area where your engineering background is a real edge."},{"f":"track14/lab.html","t":"Lab: Build a production monitor","tn":"Productionization & LLMOps","k":"12","x":"Step 1 — Generate a request log · Step 2 — The metrics that matter · Step 3 — Alert rules · Step 4 — A bad day arrives · A request log — the raw material of observability. · Percentile metrics , error rate, and daily cost. · Alert rules that turn numbers into action. · A day-over-day regression check .","s":"Averages lie. You’ll generate a realistic request log, compute the metrics that actually matter (p50, p95, error rate, cost/day), write alert rules — then simulate a bad day and watch your monitor catch a regression no average would have shown."},{"f":"track16/01-reasoning-models.html","t":"Reasoning models & test-time compute","tn":"Frontier & Responsible AI","k":"13","x":"Two ways to make a model smarter · When to reach for one (and when not) · Buy accuracy with compute · Capability comes from two levers: bigger training and more t · Reasoning models generate a long internal chain-of-thought a · It’s the trained-in, supercharged version of Track 2’s chain · They’re slower and pricier — use them for genuinely hard pro · This is model routing (Track 8) by difficulty: hard → reason · reasoning model · chain-of-thought · test-time compute","s":"A major shift in the field: instead of only making models bigger, we now let them think longer at answer time. Understanding “reasoning models” and “test-time compute” keeps you current and helps you choose the right model for a job."},{"f":"track16/02-modern-frontier.html","t":"The modern frontier","tn":"Frontier & Responsible AI","k":"13","x":"The shifts worth tracking · Open vs closed: a real design choice · Track directions, not headlines : long context, stronger age · Long context ≠ the end of RAG — retrieval still keeps contex · Small & open-weight models make cheap, private, local AI inc · Open vs closed is a real trade-off: control/privacy/cost vs  · The frontier is a toolbox of capabilities to compose , not a · open-weight · closed","s":"The field moves fast enough that specifics go stale in months. This lesson isn’t a news roundup — it’s a durable map of the shifts that matter to a builder, and a way to stay current without drowning in hype."},{"f":"track16/03-bias-fairness.html","t":"Responsible AI: bias & fairness","tn":"Frontier & Responsible AI","k":"13","x":"Why models are biased · You can’t manage what you don’t measure · Reducing it (defense in depth, again) · Find the gap the average hides · Models inherit bias from human training data — it’s a mirror · Harm becomes real when the system makes or influences decisi · Measure with disaggregated evaluation (per group), and test  · Reduce it in layers: data, prompting, output checks, human o · Sometimes the responsible choice is to assist a human, not a · model card","s":"Models learn from human data, so they inherit human biases. If your system touches decisions about people — hiring, lending, content, access — that isn’t an abstract ethics topic; it’s an engineering requirement you’ll be asked about. This lesson is practical: where bias comes from, how to measure it, and how to reduce it."},{"f":"track16/04-governance-regulation.html","t":"Governance & regulation","tn":"Frontier & Responsible AI","k":"13","x":"The organizing idea: risk-based rules · The tiers, and what they mean for you · Modern AI regulation is risk-based : obligations scale with  · Tiers: unacceptable (banned) → high-risk (strict rules) → li · High-risk (hiring, credit, medical, etc.) demands documentat · Know your tier early — it dictates what you must build; retr · Also mind data-privacy law (GDPR), copyright, and sector rul · obligations scale with risk","s":"“Be responsible” is becoming “comply with the law.” You don’t need to be a lawyer, but you do need to understand how AI regulation is structured, because it shapes what you’re allowed to build and what you must document. This is the literacy interviewers increasingly expect."},{"f":"track16/05-interview.html","t":"Interview check: Frontier & Responsible AI","tn":"Frontier & Responsible AI","k":"13","x":"The questions teams ask · Rapid-fire self-check · Reasoning models / test-time compute , and routing by task d · Why long context complements rather than replaces RAG . · Open vs closed models: privacy, cost, control vs peak capabi · Bias : where it comes from, disaggregated evaluation, and la · Risk-based regulation (tiers), and that high-risk overlaps w · The two-layer way to stay current: deep fundamentals, specif","s":"These questions test something subtle: not just whether you can build, but whether you have judgment — about new capabilities, trade-offs, and the consequences of what you ship. This is often what separates a senior hire from a mid one."},{"f":"track16/lab.html","t":"Lab: Catch bias with disaggregated evaluation","tn":"Frontier & Responsible AI","k":"13","x":"Step 1 — Build matched pairs · Step 2 — Two screeners · Step 3 — The number that hides the problem · Step 4 — Gate on the gap, not the average · Matched-pair test cases that isolate a single variable. · Disaggregated accuracy — the measurement the aggregate hides · A disparity metric with a hard gate. · The judgment to decline to automate when the gap won't close","s":"A screening model reports 83% accuracy and everyone celebrates. You’ll build the evaluation that looks underneath that number — and find the group it quietly fails, using matched candidates whose only difference is their name."},{"f":"track10/01-rag-assistant.html","t":"RAG assistant over your docs","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"What you’re building · Step 1 — Ingest: chunk, embed, store · Step 2 — Answer: retrieve, ground, cite · Step 3 — Evaluate (the part that wins) · Ship the eval. The golden set + the two numbers are your dif · Abstain honestly. The “I don’t know” path proves you handle  · Cite sources. Show which documents each answer came from — t · Write a README with your design decisions (chunk size, k, wh · It’s $0 and runnable from a clean clone — any reviewer can t","s":"Your flagship project: a grounded, cited question-answering assistant over documents you provide, with a real evaluation. It runs entirely free and local, demonstrates Tracks 1–8 in one artifact, and is the single best thing to show in an interview. Build it, and you can talk about every topic in this course from experience."},{"f":"track10/02-tool-using-agent.html","t":"A tool-using agent","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"What you’re building · Step 1 — Define tools (and mark the risky one) · Step 2 — The guarded agent loop · Every guard is present and labeled : max-steps, allowlist, a · Least privilege : the risky send_email tool isn’t even adver · The trace prints each action — you can show the reason → act · It runs free and local , and you can narrate exactly how inj","s":"Build an agent that actually does things: a guarded ReAct loop that calls real tools (a calculator and a lookup), reasons over the results, and refuses to run away or do anything dangerous. It demonstrates Track 4 end to end and shows you can give a model autonomy responsibly — runs free on local models."},{"f":"track10/03-eval-harness.html","t":"A prompt/RAG eval harness","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"What you’re building · Step 1 — The golden set (data is the product) · Step 2 — The harness (keyword + LLM-judge + per-category) · Step 3 — The regression gate (CI for prompts) · It’s the rarest thing in any portfolio — proof you measure q · It’s reusable : point it at the RAG bot (14.1), the agent (1 · It demonstrates LLM-as-judge, per-category scoring, and a CI · It’s genuinely useful — you’ll use it on your other capstone · Free and local: the judge is the same Ollama model.","s":"This is the project that signals “senior” louder than any other, because almost no one builds it: a reusable harness that scores any prompt or RAG system against a golden set, judges fuzzy quality with an LLM, and gates changes so regressions can’t ship. It’s the measurement discipline of Track 6 turned into a tool — free and runnable."},{"f":"track10/04-finetuned-model.html","t":"A fine-tuned domain model","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"What you’re building · Step 1 — Data: your behavior as instruction→response pairs · Step 2 — QLoRA fine-tune (free GPU) · Step 3 — Evaluate vs. base (the part that proves it) · You actually fine-tuned a model — most candidates have only  · You used QLoRA on a free GPU — demonstrating you know the mo · You evaluated against the base on held-out data AND checked  · You can articulate why you fine-tuned (behavior, not knowled · The adapter is a tiny artifact you can show and explain.","s":"Fine-tune a small open model to adopt a specific behavior — a consistent format, tone, or narrow skill — using QLoRA on a free Colab GPU, then prove it improved without breaking general ability. This demonstrates Track 5 end to end and shows you can do the thing most candidates only talk about."},{"f":"track10/05-optimized-chat-service.html","t":"A cost & latency-optimized chat service","tn":"Capstones","k":"14","x":"What you’re building · The optimized service · It composes caching + routing + streaming + token budgeting  · It measures cache hit-rate, routing split, and latency — pro · You can quantify savings : “caching cut X% of calls, routing · It’s the “make it production-ready” story interviewers love  · Free and local, with two real models to demonstrate routing.","s":"The final project: a production-style chat service that wraps an LLM with the serving levers from Track 8 — caching, routing, streaming, token budgeting — and measures the savings. It’s the difference between a demo and something you could actually run at scale, and it completes your end-to-end engineer’s toolkit."},{"f":"track9/01-foundations-qa.html","t":"Foundations Q&A","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"15","x":"The bank · Lead with the mechanism , then the practical consequence (co · Reach for the recap picture : text → tokens → embeddings+att · Show judgment : mention when not to use an LLM, and how you’ · Keep it tight — 30–45 seconds per answer, then stop and let ","s":"Fundamentals are table stakes: every candidate is expected to know tokens, embeddings, context, and sampling cold. This is a rapid-fire bank to make those answers automatic. Say each one aloud before opening it — fluency, not recognition, is the goal."},{"f":"track9/02-rag-qa.html","t":"RAG Q&A","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"15","x":"The bank · Always separate retrieval vs generation — it’s the answer to · Mention evaluation unprompted (recall@k/MRR + faithfulness)  · Bring up cost/latency/scale trade-offs (ANN, hybrid, rerank- · Know the advanced levers (hybrid, reranking, query transform","s":"RAG is the single most heavily-tested topic in applied-GenAI interviews this year — end-to-end design, chunking, evaluation, and production trade-offs. This bank covers the questions teams actually ask, including the advanced ones that separate strong candidates."},{"f":"track9/03-agents-qa.html","t":"Agents Q&A","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"15","x":"The bank · State the least-autonomy principle early — show you don’t re · For any action-taking agent, volunteer the guard stack (leas · Treat tool/retrieved content as untrusted (injection) — secu · Mention evaluating agents on task suites — you can’t eyeball","s":"Agentic system-design questions are increasingly common: design something where an LLM uses tools to reason, plan, and act. Interviewers want maturity — you give a model autonomy responsibly . This bank covers the questions, with the security and “when not to” judgment that signals seniority."},{"f":"track9/04-system-design.html","t":"System design rounds","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"15","x":"What makes LLM system design different · Worked example — “Design a customer-support assistant” · LLM system design adds quality/eval, hallucination, cost, la · Use the framework: clarify → data → core design → eval → saf · Always clarify scope first (users, scale, budget, “good”) be · Bring up evaluation and failure modes unprompted — it’s the  · One support-assistant-style architecture demonstrates the en","s":"The GenAI system-design interview is its own skill. You’re no longer designing deterministic CRUD apps — you’re designing probabilistic data flows where quality, cost, and failure modes are first-class. A simple framework keeps you structured under pressure and hits everything interviewers want."},{"f":"track9/05-take-home-patterns.html","t":"Take-home patterns","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"15","x":"The common assignments (and what they’re probing) · What graders actually score · “It works” is the floor ; the differentiators are evaluation · Include an eval (golden set + metric) — the #1 thing most su · Explain your decisions and trade-offs in the README — review · Handle the messy cases (abstain, validate, don’t crash) to s · You can build a complete, runnable take-home for $0 with thi","s":"Many GenAI roles use a take-home: “build a small RAG app,” “make an eval harness,” “create a tool-using agent.” Most candidates make it work and stop there. The ones who get offers add the things that signal a real engineer — and those are exactly what this course taught you."},{"f":"track9/06-behavioral-judgment.html","t":"Behavioral & judgment","tn":"Interview Bank","k":"15","x":"Two things this round measures · The AI-judgment questions · Answer behavioral questions with STAR ; prepare 4–5 concrete · AI roles test judgment : match the tool to the problem, resp · For “a time the LLM failed,” show systematic debugging + a g · Recommending against an LLM when appropriate is a strong mat · Discuss safety/ethics concretely , and be honestly self-awar · judgment · STAR","s":"The technical rounds test what you know; the behavioral round tests how you think and work — and for AI roles, it tests judgment about a powerful, fallible technology. This is where strong engineers seal the offer, and where overconfident ones lose it."},{"f":"track11/01-study-plan.html","t":"Your study plan","tn":"Get Hired","k":"16","x":"Why a plan beats willpower · The plan, week by week · Two rules that make it work · The enemy is drift , not difficulty. A schedule with small,  · Plan ~ 10 weeks at 6–8 hrs/week , but the order and build-as · Start your flagship RAG capstone in Week 3 ; add the eval ha · Experienced engineers: compress foundations, invest in RAG,  · A weekly 20-minute review converts finished lessons into kno","s":"A course without a schedule quietly becomes a tab you never close. This lesson turns the whole curriculum into a concrete, week-by-week plan with a build attached to every phase — so you finish, and finish with proof."},{"f":"track11/02-portfolio.html","t":"Portfolio playbook","tn":"Get Hired","k":"16","x":"Why a portfolio decides it · What a hire-worthy repo contains · The README template · Where to put it, and how to point at it · Evidence > claims. A working, measured repo is what separate · Depth > breadth: one excellent flagship (the RAG assistant)  · The README sells the project — lead with the demo, decisions · An eval harness is the rarest, most senior signal you can sh · It must run from a clean clone on free/local models — pin ve","s":"Knowledge gets you through the door; evidence gets you the offer. This lesson turns your capstones into a portfolio a hiring manager can skim in two minutes and think, “this person can ship.”"},{"f":"track11/03-positioning.html","t":"Positioning your experience","tn":"Get Hired","k":"16","x":"Why framing is the biggest lever you have · Translate what you’ve done · Aim at the right roles · Framing is your biggest lever: the same history reads as “no · Production GenAI is largely data + systems work — retrieval, · Rewrite bullets to name the bridge (ETL→RAG ingestion, data  · Target applied/infra roles (AI/ML Engineer, RAG/Platform, AI · Lead with a one-line pitch : proven engineer + demonstrated ","s":"If you’re coming from data engineering, your decade of work is an asset, not a gap to apologize for — but only if you frame it right. This lesson shows how to translate what you’ve already done into the language GenAI teams are hiring for."},{"f":"track11/04-mock-interview.html","t":"Mock interview drill","tn":"Get Hired","k":"16","x":"Why rehearse out loud · How to run a realistic mock · The drill: draw a question · A few questions, with what a strong answer hits · Score yourself honestly · Interviews test retrieval under pressure + communication — r · Each round maps to a track (fundamentals→T1–2, RAG/agents→T3 · Strong technical answers follow why → how → trade-offs & fai · Prepare 4–5 STAR stories with real metrics; your data-engine · Score yourself on correctness, structure, trade-offs, delive","s":"Knowing the material and performing it under pressure are different skills. This lesson is a rehearsal: how to run a realistic mock on yourself, a mixed question drill, and a way to score your answers so practice actually improves them."},{"f":"track11/lab.html","t":"Lab: Generate your portfolio README","tn":"Get Hired","k":"16","x":"Step 1 — Describe your project · Step 2 — Generate the README · Step 3 — Score it against the hiring checklist · Step 4 — Compare with a typical README · A README generator in the shape reviewers respond to. · A scorer against the ninety-second checklist. · Proof of the gap between “a project” and evidence .","s":"This lab produces something you’ll actually use. Fill in your project, generate a README in the shape hiring managers respond to, then score it against the checklist — and watch a typical README fail it."}],"glossary":[{"term":"rag","desc":"Retrieval-Augmented Generation — retrieving relevant documents and putting them in the prompt so the model answers from real sources."},{"term":"obfuscation","desc":"Hiding a malicious instruction (via encoding, spacing, or odd phrasing) so it slips past simple filters."},{"term":"obligations scale with risk","desc":"The regulatory principle that higher-risk AI uses carry stricter requirements (documentation, oversight, testing)."},{"term":"resources","desc":"In MCP, read-only data a server exposes to a model (files, records); more broadly, materials to learn from."},{"term":"a/b test","desc":"Running two versions on live traffic at once and comparing their measured results to decide which is better."},{"term":"abstention","desc":"When a model declines to answer rather than guess — the safe move when it isn't confident or lacks grounding."},{"term":"autonomy","desc":"How much an agent is allowed to act on its own without a human approving each step."},{"term":"bm25","desc":"A classic keyword-ranking algorithm that scores documents by term frequency; strong at exact-word matches, blind to paraphrase."},{"term":"backpropagation","desc":"The algorithm that computes how to nudge each weight to reduce the loss, by propagating error backward through the network."},{"term":"batching","desc":"Processing many requests together in one pass to use the GPU efficiently and raise throughput."},{"term":"ci","desc":"Continuous integration — automated checks (tests, evals) that run on every change before it's allowed to merge."},{"term":"clip","desc":"A model trained to put images and text in one shared embedding space, so you can match pictures to captions."},{"term":"caching","desc":"Storing the answer to a request so an identical (or similar) later request returns instantly and for free."},{"term":"chain-of-thought","desc":"Prompting the model to reason step by step before answering, which improves multi-step logic and math."},{"term":"chunk size","desc":"How large each piece of a document is when split for retrieval — too small fragments ideas, too large blurs them."},{"term":"citations","desc":"References the model attaches to an answer pointing at the exact retrieved sources it used."},{"term":"cohen’s κ","desc":"Cohen's kappa — an agreement score between two raters that corrects for how often they'd agree by chance."},{"term":"cohen's κ","desc":"Cohen's kappa — an agreement score between two raters that corrects for how often they'd agree by chance."},{"term":"constrained decoding","desc":"Forcing the model's output to follow a fixed grammar or schema (e.g. valid JSON) as it generates."},{"term":"content moderation","desc":"Checking input or output for unsafe content (hate, violence, etc.) and blocking or flagging it."},{"term":"continuous batching","desc":"A serving technique that adds and removes requests from a running batch on the fly to keep the GPU busy."},{"term":"dpo","desc":"Direct Preference Optimization — a simpler alternative to RLHF that tunes a model directly on preferred-vs-rejected answer pairs."},{"term":"data minimization","desc":"Sending and storing only the personal data you actually need — a core privacy principle."},{"term":"decomposition","desc":"Breaking a hard task into smaller sub-tasks the model can handle one at a time."},{"term":"defense in depth","desc":"Layering several imperfect safeguards so the system stays safe even when any one layer is bypassed."},{"term":"dense retrieval","desc":"Finding relevant text by comparing embedding vectors (meaning) rather than matching keywords."},{"term":"direct injection","desc":"A prompt-injection attack where the malicious instruction is typed straight into the user input."},{"term":"document ai","desc":"Turning documents (scans, PDFs, forms) into structured data — extraction, OCR, and validation."},{"term":"evals","desc":"Systematic tests that measure whether a model or system actually works, against a fixed set of cases."},{"term":"eval","desc":"A systematic test that measures whether a model or system actually works, against a fixed set of cases."},{"term":"faithfulness","desc":"Whether an answer is actually supported by the retrieved context, rather than invented."},{"term":"fine-tuning","desc":"Continuing to train a pretrained model on your own examples to teach it a specific style or behavior."},{"term":"gguf","desc":"A file format for packaging quantized models so they run efficiently on consumer hardware (e.g. with llama.cpp)."},{"term":"gpu","desc":"Graphics processing unit — the parallel hardware that makes training and running large models fast."},{"term":"google colab","desc":"A free, browser-based notebook from Google with a GPU attached — no install needed."},{"term":"greedy decoding","desc":"Always picking the single highest-probability next token; deterministic but can be repetitive."},{"term":"grounding","desc":"Tying a model's answer to real retrieved sources so it states facts from documents, not from memory."},{"term":"hybrid search","desc":"Combining dense (embedding) and sparse (keyword) retrieval to get the strengths of both."},{"term":"indirect injection","desc":"A prompt-injection attack hidden inside content the model later retrieves (a web page, a document)."},{"term":"input moderation","desc":"Screening the user's input for unsafe or malicious content before the model sees it."},{"term":"instruction tuning","desc":"Fine-tuning a base model on instruction→response pairs so it learns to follow requests."},{"term":"json","desc":"JavaScript Object Notation — a simple, universal text format for structured data (keys and values)."},{"term":"llm-as-judge","desc":"Using one LLM to score another model's outputs against a rubric, instead of a human grading each one."},{"term":"latency","desc":"How long a request takes to respond — a core user-experience and cost metric."},{"term":"least privilege","desc":"Giving a tool or agent only the minimum permissions it needs, so a compromise can't do much damage."},{"term":"llama guard","desc":"An open safety classifier from Meta that labels text as safe or unsafe across categories."},{"term":"lora","desc":"Low-Rank Adaptation — fine-tuning by training two small matrices beside the frozen model, so under 1% of weights change."},{"term":"long-term memory","desc":"Information an agent stores across sessions (in a database or vector store), beyond the current conversation."},{"term":"mcp","desc":"Model Context Protocol — an open standard for connecting models to tools and data sources in a uniform way."},{"term":"mcp host/client","desc":"The application (and its client library) that talks to MCP servers on the model's behalf."},{"term":"mcp server","desc":"A service that exposes tools or data to models over the Model Context Protocol."},{"term":"mrr","desc":"Mean Reciprocal Rank — a retrieval metric rewarding systems that place the right result nearer the top."},{"term":"maximal marginal relevance","desc":"A selection method that picks results which are relevant but also different from each other, reducing redundancy."},{"term":"model routing","desc":"Sending each request to the cheapest model that can handle it, escalating to a bigger one only when needed."},{"term":"monitoring","desc":"Watching a live system's metrics (latency, cost, errors, quality) to catch problems as they happen."},{"term":"multimodal rag","desc":"Retrieval-augmented generation over more than text — images, tables, audio — matched in a shared space."},{"term":"ocr","desc":"Optical character recognition — turning an image of text into machine-readable characters."},{"term":"observability","desc":"Being able to see inside a running system — traces, logs, metrics — well enough to debug why something happened."},{"term":"offline evaluation","desc":"Testing against a fixed golden set before shipping, to catch regressions; reproducible and gate-able."},{"term":"offline eval","desc":"Testing against a fixed golden set before shipping, to catch regressions; reproducible and gate-able."},{"term":"ollama","desc":"A free tool for downloading and running open-weight models locally with one command."},{"term":"online eval","desc":"Measuring quality on real production traffic to catch drift and issues a fixed test set can't."},{"term":"online evaluation","desc":"Measuring quality on real production traffic to catch drift and issues a fixed test set can't."},{"term":"online evals","desc":"Measuring quality on real production traffic to catch drift and issues a fixed test set can't."},{"term":"online evals at scale","desc":"Running automated quality checks (often LLM-as-judge) on a sample of live traffic continuously."},{"term":"output validation","desc":"Checking the model's output against a schema or rules before you trust or act on it."},{"term":"overlap","desc":"How many characters/tokens adjacent chunks share, so a fact on a boundary isn't split apart."},{"term":"peft","desc":"Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning — a family of methods (like LoRA) that train a tiny fraction of the weights."},{"term":"pii","desc":"Personally identifiable information — data that identifies a person (name, email, ID), which must be handled carefully."},{"term":"perceived latency","desc":"How fast a response feels, driven by time-to-first-token — streaming improves it without changing total time."},{"term":"plan-then-execute","desc":"An agent pattern that drafts a full plan first, then carries out the steps, for cleaner and cheaper traces."},{"term":"planning","desc":"An agent deciding a sequence of steps toward a goal before acting."},{"term":"pointwise","desc":"Judging each item on its own against a rubric, rather than comparing two items head-to-head."},{"term":"preference tuning","desc":"Training a model on human preferences (which answer is better) to align its behavior — e.g. RLHF or DPO."},{"term":"prompt engineering","desc":"Designing the instructions, examples, and format you give a model to get reliable results."},{"term":"prompt injection","desc":"An attack where malicious text tricks the model into ignoring its instructions and following the attacker's."},{"term":"prompt versioning","desc":"Tracking prompts like code — versions, diffs, and eval results — so changes are reviewable and reversible."},{"term":"prompt/prefix caching","desc":"Reusing the processed form of a shared prompt prefix so repeated calls skip re-computing it, cutting cost and latency."},{"term":"qlora","desc":"Quantized LoRA — LoRA fine-tuning on top of a 4-bit quantized base model, so it fits on a single small GPU."},{"term":"quantization","desc":"Storing model weights at lower precision (e.g. 4-bit) to shrink memory and speed inference, for a small quality cost."},{"term":"query transformation","desc":"Rewriting or expanding a user's query (rephrasing, sub-questions, HyDE) to retrieve better."},{"term":"rlhf","desc":"Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback — aligning a model using a reward model trained on human preferences."},{"term":"react","desc":"An agent loop that alternates Reasoning and Acting: think, call a tool, observe the result, repeat."},{"term":"reciprocal rank fusion","desc":"Combining several ranked result lists into one by summing reciprocal ranks — a simple, strong fusion method."},{"term":"redaction","desc":"Removing or masking sensitive data (like PII) from text before it's sent or stored."},{"term":"reference-based","desc":"An eval that compares an output to a known correct answer."},{"term":"retention limits","desc":"Rules for how long data may be kept before it must be deleted."},{"term":"retrieval","desc":"Fetching the most relevant pieces of your data for a query, so the model can answer from them."},{"term":"retrieval-augmented generation","desc":"RAG — retrieving relevant documents and putting them in the prompt so the model answers from real sources."},{"term":"star","desc":"A behavioral-interview answer structure: Situation, Task, Action, Result."},{"term":"short-term memory","desc":"What an agent keeps within the current conversation — the running context of the task."},{"term":"sparse retrieval","desc":"Keyword-based retrieval (like BM25) that matches literal terms rather than meaning."},{"term":"speech-to-text","desc":"Transcribing spoken audio into written text (also called ASR)."},{"term":"streaming","desc":"Sending the model's output token by token as it's generated, so the user sees words appear immediately."},{"term":"structured output","desc":"Making the model return machine-readable data (like JSON) instead of free prose."},{"term":"supervised fine-tuning","desc":"SFT — fine-tuning on labeled input→output examples, the first stage of turning a base model into an assistant."},{"term":"temperature","desc":"A dial that reshapes the model's probability distribution before sampling — low is focused, high is creative."},{"term":"text-to-sql","desc":"Turning a plain-English question into a database query."},{"term":"text-to-speech","desc":"Generating spoken audio from written text."},{"term":"throughput","desc":"How many requests or tokens a system handles per second — the capacity metric."},{"term":"time to first token","desc":"How long until the first output token appears — what makes streaming feel fast."},{"term":"token budgeting","desc":"Deciding how many tokens to spend on context vs output to control cost and stay within limits."},{"term":"tool calling","desc":"The model emitting a structured request to run a function; your code runs it and returns the result."},{"term":"top-k","desc":"Sampling only from the k most likely next tokens (retrieval: keeping the k nearest results)."},{"term":"top-p","desc":"Nucleus sampling — sampling from the smallest set of tokens whose probabilities sum to p."},{"term":"validation","desc":"Checking that data or output meets the rules you require before trusting it."},{"term":"xss","desc":"Cross-site scripting — injecting malicious scripts into a web page; a risk when model output is rendered as HTML."},{"term":"adapter","desc":"A small set of trained weights (as in LoRA) added beside a frozen model to change its behavior; shippable as a tiny file."},{"term":"agent","desc":"An LLM that can take actions — call tools, observe results, and loop — to accomplish a goal, not just chat."},{"term":"agent loop","desc":"The cycle an agent repeats: reason, take an action (tool call), observe the result, until it can answer."},{"term":"agreement","desc":"How often two judges (human or model) give the same verdict — used to validate an LLM judge."},{"term":"alerts","desc":"Automated notifications that fire when a monitored metric crosses a threshold."},{"term":"allowlisting","desc":"Permitting only an explicit, known-safe set of things (e.g. SELECT-only SQL) and rejecting everything else."},{"term":"answer relevance","desc":"Whether the answer actually addresses the question that was asked."},{"term":"approximate nearest neighbor","desc":"ANN — fast index methods (like HNSW) that find near-closest vectors without scanning them all, trading a little recall for big speed."},{"term":"argument validation","desc":"Checking a tool call's arguments (types, ranges, permissions) before executing it."},{"term":"arguments","desc":"The input values passed to a function or tool."},{"term":"arms race","desc":"The ongoing back-and-forth between attackers finding new exploits and defenders patching them."},{"term":"assets","desc":"The files that make up the site (scripts, styles, images) served to the browser."},{"term":"assistant messages","desc":"Turns in a chat authored by the model, part of the conversation history."},{"term":"attacker goals","desc":"What an attacker is trying to achieve (exfiltrate data, run an action) — the thing your threat model defends against."},{"term":"attention","desc":"The mechanism that lets each token weigh every other token to decide which context matters for the next prediction."},{"term":"autoregression","desc":"Generating one token at a time and feeding it back in — the loop behind all text generation."},{"term":"base model","desc":"A pretrained next-token predictor before instruction tuning — knowledgeable but not yet a helpful assistant."},{"term":"baseline","desc":"The current version you compare a change against to decide if it's actually an improvement."},{"term":"bi-encoder","desc":"An encoder that embeds query and document separately, so document vectors can be precomputed and searched fast."},{"term":"budgets & timeouts","desc":"Hard limits on steps, tokens, or time so an agent can't run away and burn money."},{"term":"budgets &amp; timeouts","desc":"Hard limits on steps, tokens, or time so an agent can't run away and burn money."},{"term":"byte-pair encoding","desc":"BPE — a tokenizer that builds sub-word units by repeatedly merging the most frequent character pairs."},{"term":"cascade","desc":"Trying a cheap model first and only escalating to an expensive one when needed."},{"term":"catastrophic forgetting","desc":"When fine-tuning on new data makes a model lose abilities it previously had."},{"term":"cell","desc":"One executable block of code in a notebook."},{"term":"chat","desc":"The conversational interface where user and model exchange messages."},{"term":"chat format","desc":"The structure of a conversation as a list of role-tagged messages (system/user/assistant)."},{"term":"chat template","desc":"The exact way roles and messages are formatted into the string a chat model expects."},{"term":"chunk","desc":"A single piece a document is split into for embedding and retrieval."},{"term":"chunks","desc":"The pieces a document is split into for embedding and retrieval."},{"term":"closed","desc":"A closed (API-only) model — high capability with no infra, but you send data out and can't control versioning."},{"term":"container","desc":"A packaged, isolated runtime (e.g. Docker) that bundles an app with its dependencies so it runs anywhere."},{"term":"context window","desc":"The maximum amount of text (in tokens) a model can consider at once."},{"term":"cosine similarity","desc":"A score for how aligned two vectors are, based on the angle between them — the core of embedding search."},{"term":"cost/quality frontier","desc":"The trade-off curve between how much you spend and how good the output is; you pick a point on it."},{"term":"cross-encoder","desc":"A model that reads a query and a document together and scores their relevance — accurate but slower than a bi-encoder."},{"term":"cross-encoder reranker","desc":"A cross-encoder used as a second stage to reorder the top retrieved results by true relevance."},{"term":"decode","desc":"The generation phase where output tokens are produced one at a time (serial, the slow part)."},{"term":"decoding","desc":"The overall process of choosing output tokens from the model's probabilities."},{"term":"default argument","desc":"A function parameter's fallback value used when the caller doesn't supply one."},{"term":"dictionary","desc":"A Python data structure mapping keys to values."},{"term":"dimension","desc":"One coordinate of an embedding vector; a vector has many dimensions capturing different aspects of meaning."},{"term":"distillation","desc":"Training a small model to imitate a larger one, keeping much of the quality at lower cost."},{"term":"drift","desc":"When live inputs or the world change over time so a model's quality quietly degrades."},{"term":"early stopping","desc":"Halting training when validation performance stops improving, to avoid overfitting."},{"term":"edge cases","desc":"Unusual inputs at the boundaries of expected behavior — where bugs and failures hide."},{"term":"embedding","desc":"A list of numbers representing a piece of text's meaning, so similarity becomes geometry."},{"term":"embedding model","desc":"A model that turns text into embedding vectors for search and comparison."},{"term":"end-to-end metrics","desc":"Measures of the whole system's output quality, as opposed to one component in isolation."},{"term":"environment variables","desc":"Configuration values (like API keys) supplied to a program by its environment, kept out of the code."},{"term":"episodic memory","desc":"An agent's record of specific past events or interactions it can recall."},{"term":"epoch","desc":"One full pass over the training dataset."},{"term":"eval gate","desc":"A rule that blocks a change from shipping if it fails any eval case — especially a previously-passing one."},{"term":"eval suite","desc":"The full collection of eval cases a system is tested against."},{"term":"exact cache","desc":"A cache keyed on the exact input string — a hit only when the request is identical."},{"term":"example pairs","desc":"Input→output examples used for few-shot prompting or fine-tuning."},{"term":"f-string","desc":"A Python string with embedded expressions, written f\"...{value}...\"."},{"term":"few-shot","desc":"Giving the model a few examples in the prompt so it follows the pattern."},{"term":"few-shot cot","desc":"Few-shot prompting where the examples themselves show step-by-step reasoning."},{"term":"for-loop","desc":"A loop that repeats a block of code once for each item in a sequence."},{"term":"forward pass","desc":"Running input through the network once to produce an output (no learning)."},{"term":"function","desc":"A named, reusable block of code that takes inputs and returns a result."},{"term":"fuses","desc":"Safety cut-offs (like step limits or spend caps) that stop a runaway process."},{"term":"gate","desc":"A checkpoint that must pass before a change proceeds — e.g. an eval gate before deploy."},{"term":"general-ability","desc":"A model's broad, all-round capability, as opposed to skill on one narrow task."},{"term":"golden set","desc":"A fixed, human-curated set of test cases with known-good answers, used to measure quality and catch regressions."},{"term":"gradient","desc":"The direction and size of the change to each weight that would most reduce the loss."},{"term":"gradient descent","desc":"The training loop that repeatedly nudges weights down the loss gradient to improve the model."},{"term":"guard","desc":"A check or safeguard placed around a model or tool to prevent unsafe behavior."},{"term":"hallucination","desc":"When a model states something fluent and confident but false or unsupported."},{"term":"handoff","desc":"Passing a task from one agent (or from an agent to a human) to another."},{"term":"held out","desc":"Data deliberately kept out of training so it can honestly measure generalization."},{"term":"held-out set","desc":"A dataset kept separate from training, used to evaluate real performance."},{"term":"hit rate","desc":"The fraction of queries for which retrieval returned at least one correct result."},{"term":"human-in-the-loop","desc":"Keeping a person in the decision path to approve or review consequential actions."},{"term":"if-statement","desc":"A branch that runs code only when a condition is true."},{"term":"in-context learning","desc":"A model adapting its behavior purely from examples in the prompt, without any weight updates."},{"term":"index","desc":"A data structure that makes retrieval fast; also, a position in a list."},{"term":"index time","desc":"The one-time, offline phase where documents are chunked, embedded, and stored."},{"term":"inference","desc":"Running a trained, frozen model to produce outputs — it doesn't learn anything while doing so."},{"term":"instruction → response","desc":"The input→output shape of the examples used to instruction-tune a model."},{"term":"instruction-tuned","desc":"A model that's been fine-tuned to follow instructions, turning a base model into a usable assistant."},{"term":"jailbreak","desc":"A crafted prompt that gets a model to bypass its own safety rules."},{"term":"judgment","desc":"The senior skill of choosing the right approach and foreseeing failure modes — not just knowing facts."},{"term":"knowledge base","desc":"The corpus of documents a RAG system retrieves from."},{"term":"knowledge cutoff","desc":"The date after which a model has no training knowledge of the world."},{"term":"language model","desc":"A model that predicts the next token, and from that can generate and understand text."},{"term":"large language model","desc":"A very large next-token predictor trained on huge text corpora — an LLM."},{"term":"leak checks","desc":"Tests that catch sensitive data (secrets, PII) escaping in outputs or logs."},{"term":"learning rate","desc":"How big a step training takes when adjusting weights — too high overshoots, too low crawls."},{"term":"least-privilege tools","desc":"Tools scoped to the minimum permissions needed, so misuse causes limited harm."},{"term":"libraries","desc":"Reusable packages of code you import instead of writing yourself."},{"term":"list","desc":"An ordered, changeable collection of items in Python."},{"term":"list comprehension","desc":"A concise Python expression that builds a list from a loop in one line."},{"term":"living","desc":"A document or set that's kept continuously updated rather than frozen."},{"term":"logits","desc":"The raw, pre-softmax scores a model assigns to each possible next token."},{"term":"loss","desc":"A number measuring how wrong the model's predictions are; training minimizes it."},{"term":"max output tokens","desc":"A cap on how many tokens the model may generate in a response."},{"term":"messages","desc":"The role-tagged turns (system/user/assistant) that make up a chat."},{"term":"metadata filtering","desc":"Restricting retrieval to documents matching structured fields (date, author, type) alongside vector search."},{"term":"metric","desc":"A number you measure to judge quality or performance."},{"term":"model card","desc":"A short document describing a model's intended use, training, limitations, and known risks."},{"term":"multi-agent","desc":"A system where several specialized agents collaborate, often coordinated by an orchestrator."},{"term":"multi-turn escalation","desc":"An attack that builds across several messages rather than one, gradually pushing past guardrails."},{"term":"normalizes","desc":"Scales values to a standard range (e.g. unit-length vectors) so comparisons are fair."},{"term":"notebook","desc":"An interactive document of code and text cells you run one at a time (e.g. Jupyter, Colab)."},{"term":"nucleus sampling","desc":"Top-p sampling — drawing from the smallest set of tokens whose probability mass reaches p."},{"term":"one-shot","desc":"Prompting with exactly one example."},{"term":"open-weight","desc":"A model whose weights are published so you can run and fine-tune it yourself."},{"term":"orchestration pattern","desc":"A design for how multiple agents or steps are coordinated (router, pipeline, planner, etc.)."},{"term":"orchestrator","desc":"The controller that routes work among tools or sub-agents and assembles the result."},{"term":"outcome metrics","desc":"Measures of whether the real goal was achieved, not just intermediate steps."},{"term":"output moderation","desc":"Screening the model's output for unsafe content before it reaches the user."},{"term":"overfitting","desc":"When a model memorizes training quirks instead of learning general patterns — train loss falls but validation loss rises."},{"term":"override","desc":"Replacing an inherited or default behavior with your own."},{"term":"pairwise","desc":"Judging by comparing two outputs head-to-head and picking the better one."},{"term":"parameters","desc":"The learned weights of a model; also, the inputs a function accepts."},{"term":"patches","desc":"Fixes applied to close a known vulnerability or bug."},{"term":"persistence","desc":"Storing data so it survives beyond the current run or session."},{"term":"plan-and-reflect","desc":"An agent pattern that plans, acts, then critiques its own work and revises."},{"term":"precision","desc":"Of the results you returned, the fraction that were actually relevant."},{"term":"precision@k","desc":"Precision measured over just the top k retrieved results."},{"term":"prefill","desc":"The phase where the model reads the whole input prompt in one parallel pass (fast, cheap per token)."},{"term":"prompt","desc":"The full text you send the model — instructions, context, and question."},{"term":"prompt hardening","desc":"Strengthening a prompt against injection with delimiters, instruction hierarchy, and refusal rules."},{"term":"prompts","desc":"The texts you send the model to elicit responses."},{"term":"quantizes","desc":"Converts weights to lower precision to save memory and speed inference."},{"term":"query time","desc":"The per-request phase where a query is embedded and matched against the index."},{"term":"rank","desc":"A result's position in an ordered list; retrieval quality depends on where the right item ranks."},{"term":"reasoning model","desc":"A model trained to spend extra inference-time compute 'thinking' before answering, boosting hard-problem accuracy."},{"term":"recall","desc":"Of all the relevant items that exist, the fraction your system actually found."},{"term":"recall@k","desc":"Recall measured within the top k retrieved results — did the right document make the cut?"},{"term":"red-teaming","desc":"Deliberately attacking your own system to find weaknesses before real attackers do."},{"term":"reference-free","desc":"An eval that scores an output on its own (e.g. faithfulness) without a known correct answer."},{"term":"regression / catastrophic forgetting","desc":"A model losing previously-working behavior after a change or further training."},{"term":"regression test","desc":"A test that guards against a specific past failure coming back."},{"term":"representative","desc":"A test set that reflects the real distribution of inputs, so results generalize."},{"term":"reranker","desc":"A second-stage model that reorders retrieved results by true relevance."},{"term":"retrieval metrics","desc":"Measures of retrieval quality — recall@k, precision@k, MRR — judged separately from answer quality."},{"term":"return value","desc":"The result a function hands back to its caller."},{"term":"role","desc":"A message's author tag in a chat (system, user, or assistant)."},{"term":"role-play","desc":"An attack (or technique) that gets a model to act as a character to change its behavior."},{"term":"router","desc":"A component that sends each request to the right model, tool, or agent."},{"term":"rubric","desc":"The explicit criteria a judge uses to score outputs consistently."},{"term":"sampling","desc":"Randomly drawing the next token from the model's probability distribution, shaped by temperature/top-p."},{"term":"sanitization","desc":"Cleaning input or output to remove dangerous content before it's used."},{"term":"schema","desc":"A formal description of a data structure's fields and types (e.g. for JSON or a database)."},{"term":"schema validation","desc":"Checking that data matches its declared schema before trusting it."},{"term":"seed","desc":"A fixed number that makes randomness reproducible across runs."},{"term":"self-attention","desc":"Attention applied within one sequence, letting each token attend to the others — the core of the transformer."},{"term":"self-consistency","desc":"Sampling several reasoning paths and taking the majority answer to boost reliability."},{"term":"self-supervised learning","desc":"Training where the data supplies its own labels — e.g. predict the next token — so no human labeling is needed, which is why it scales to the whole web."},{"term":"semantic cache","desc":"A cache that returns a stored answer when a new query is close in meaning, not just identical."},{"term":"semantic memory","desc":"An agent's store of general facts and knowledge, as opposed to specific episodes."},{"term":"softmax","desc":"The function that turns raw logits into a probability distribution over tokens."},{"term":"span","desc":"A contiguous stretch of text (e.g. the characters a value occupies)."},{"term":"specialist","desc":"A model or agent focused on one narrow domain or task."},{"term":"specialist agents","desc":"Multiple narrow agents each handling part of a task, coordinated together."},{"term":"step","desc":"One iteration of an agent loop, or one line of a plan."},{"term":"step limit","desc":"A hard cap on how many loop iterations an agent may run before stopping."},{"term":"stopping condition","desc":"The rule that ends an agent loop — goal met, step budget hit, or repeat detected."},{"term":"string","desc":"A piece of text in code."},{"term":"system message","desc":"The instruction at the top of a chat that sets the model's role and rules, outranking user text."},{"term":"task metric","desc":"A measure of success on the specific task, e.g. exact-match or task completion rate."},{"term":"test-time compute","desc":"Extra computation spent at inference (more reasoning, sampling, or self-checking) to improve answers."},{"term":"threat model","desc":"An explicit description of who might attack, what they want, and what you're defending — the basis of security design."},{"term":"token","desc":"The unit a model reads and generates — a word piece, not a whole word."},{"term":"token budget","desc":"The tokens you allot to context and output to control cost and stay within limits."},{"term":"tokenizer","desc":"The component that splits text into tokens and maps them to ids."},{"term":"tokens","desc":"The sub-word units a model reads and generates."},{"term":"tool","desc":"An external function an agent can call — search, a calculator, an API, a database."},{"term":"tool call","desc":"The model's structured request to run a specific tool with given arguments."},{"term":"tool result","desc":"The output your code returns to the model after running a tool it called."},{"term":"tool schema","desc":"The declared name, description, and argument types that tell a model how to call a tool."},{"term":"tools","desc":"External functions an agent can call to act on the world or fetch information."},{"term":"trace","desc":"The full recorded detail of one request — prompt, retrieval, tool calls, output — used to debug it."},{"term":"traceback","desc":"Python's printout of where and how an error occurred."},{"term":"tracing","desc":"Recording each request's full execution so you can inspect and debug it later."},{"term":"training","desc":"Adjusting a model's weights on data to reduce its loss."},{"term":"training example","desc":"A single input→output pair the model learns from."},{"term":"training set","desc":"The data a model learns its weights from."},{"term":"trajectory","desc":"The full sequence of steps an agent took on a task."},{"term":"transformer","desc":"The neural-network architecture behind modern LLMs, built on self-attention."},{"term":"trust boundary","desc":"The line between data you control and untrusted input; anything crossing it must be treated as hostile."},{"term":"try/except","desc":"Python's way to catch and handle an error instead of crashing."},{"term":"two-stage retrieval","desc":"Retrieve a broad candidate set fast, then rerank the top few precisely."},{"term":"untrusted inputs","desc":"Any data from outside your control (user text, web pages, documents) that could carry an attack."},{"term":"user feedback","desc":"Signals from real users (thumbs up/down, re-asks) used to measure and improve quality."},{"term":"user messages","desc":"The turns in a chat authored by the user."},{"term":"user profile","desc":"Stored facts about a user an agent uses to personalize its behavior."},{"term":"vllm","desc":"A high-throughput open-source serving engine for LLMs, known for fast batched inference."},{"term":"validate","desc":"Check that something meets the required rules before trusting it."},{"term":"validation set","desc":"Held-out data used during development to tune and check a model without touching the test set."},{"term":"value","desc":"A piece of data (a number, string, etc.); also what a dictionary key maps to."},{"term":"variable","desc":"A named container that holds a value in code."},{"term":"vector","desc":"A list of numbers; an embedding is a vector representing meaning."},{"term":"vector database","desc":"A store built to index and search embedding vectors by similarity at scale."},{"term":"vision encoder","desc":"The part of a multimodal model that turns an image into vectors the language model can use."},{"term":"vision-language model","desc":"A model that takes both images and text and reasons over them together."},{"term":"visual question answering","desc":"Answering a text question about the contents of an image."},{"term":"vocabulary","desc":"The fixed set of tokens a model knows."},{"term":"web service","desc":"A program that answers requests over the network (e.g. an HTTP API)."},{"term":"weights","desc":"The learned numbers inside a model — its parameters — fixed after training."},{"term":"zero-shot","desc":"Prompting with no examples, relying on the model's pretrained ability."},{"term":"zero-shot cot","desc":"Triggering step-by-step reasoning with no examples, e.g. by adding \"think step by step\"."},{"term":"“lost in the middle”","desc":"The tendency of models to overlook facts buried in the middle of a long context."},{"term":"lost in the middle","desc":"The tendency of models to overlook facts buried in the middle of a long context."}]};
